00:04:34.960 --> 00:04:38.770
So, pulque is an alcoholic
beverage, which is made

00:04:38.770 --> 00:04:41.080
by fermenting the sap
of the maguey plant,

00:04:41.080 --> 00:04:43.690
which is also called the agave,
and here we have a picture.

00:04:43.690 --> 00:04:47.110
And then this is--
And then this is a--

00:04:47.110 --> 00:04:49.380
This is a picture
of a [inaudible],

00:04:49.380 --> 00:04:53.290
a person who is taking the
sap from the maguey plant

00:04:53.290 --> 00:04:57.150
through a gourd and then the
sap will be made into pulque.

00:04:57.150 --> 00:05:01.530
Mesoamericans have been drinking
pulque for probably millennia.

00:05:01.530 --> 00:05:03.860
There is some debate
about how old it is.

00:05:03.860 --> 00:05:06.710
Although its popularity has
waxed and waned, particularly

00:05:06.710 --> 00:05:09.600
in the past hundred years or so.

00:05:09.600 --> 00:05:12.430
Pulque is quite perishable
so it usually only last

00:05:12.430 --> 00:05:14.310
for a few days, maybe
up to a week

00:05:14.310 --> 00:05:16.410
after it's finished fermenting.

00:05:16.410 --> 00:05:18.970
Although recently some
companies have begun canning it

00:05:18.970 --> 00:05:20.940
for export.

00:05:20.940 --> 00:05:22.570
And so here we have
Pulque La Lucha,

00:05:22.570 --> 00:05:23.870
and we'll come back to that.

00:05:23.870 --> 00:05:26.810
The alcohol level varies,
so I think it can be

00:05:26.810 --> 00:05:29.780
as low as 2 to 3% alcohol.

00:05:29.780 --> 00:05:34.220
I looked at public health
records from the early nine--

00:05:34.220 --> 00:05:36.370
the early 20th century in
Mexico City, and there,

00:05:36.370 --> 00:05:38.330
the alcohol content
seemed to be like 3 to 4%.

00:05:38.330 --> 00:05:42.130
I think that this canned
pulque is 5% alcohol.

00:05:42.130 --> 00:05:44.760
So probably for as long as
people have been talking

00:05:44.760 --> 00:05:46.880
about pulque, they've
been arguing about issues

00:05:46.880 --> 00:05:48.670
of moderation and abuse.

00:05:48.670 --> 00:05:53.420
So in the 1540s, friar
Toribio de Motolinia said

00:05:53.420 --> 00:05:57.090
that pulque made indigenous
people "violently drunk

00:05:57.090 --> 00:05:59.970
and accordingly more
cruel and bestial".

00:05:59.970 --> 00:06:02.030
Although he then went on
to say, actually, however,

00:06:02.030 --> 00:06:03.460
if taken with moderation,

00:06:03.460 --> 00:06:06.110
pulque is wholesome
and very nutritious.

00:06:06.110 --> 00:06:07.750
And this is this
contrast you see

00:06:07.750 --> 00:06:09.110
in a lot of-- I have
many examples.

00:06:09.110 --> 00:06:11.370
So you can see here
in this quotation,

00:06:11.370 --> 00:06:13.270
in addition to the issues
of moderation and abuse,

00:06:13.270 --> 00:06:15.140
you can see that Spaniards,

00:06:15.140 --> 00:06:18.520
as well as indigenous people saw
this as an indigenous product

00:06:18.520 --> 00:06:21.430
that was consumed by indigenous
people, although in fact

00:06:21.430 --> 00:06:25.980
like everybody drink it in
many different settings.

00:06:25.980 --> 00:06:28.540
This multilinea quotation
also points to the fact

00:06:28.540 --> 00:06:31.340
that colonial chroniclers
tended to discuss pulque

00:06:31.340 --> 00:06:33.660
through categories of
order and disorder,

00:06:33.660 --> 00:06:35.910
purity and mixture
and health and vice.

00:06:35.910 --> 00:06:38.490
So as Mary Douglas and
others have explained,

00:06:38.490 --> 00:06:40.150
these sorts of ideas
about purity

00:06:40.150 --> 00:06:43.110
and pollution are often
used to maintain boundaries

00:06:43.110 --> 00:06:45.290
and reinforce social
hierarchies.

00:06:45.290 --> 00:06:46.780
And this connection
between purity

00:06:46.780 --> 00:06:49.130
and social order is
particularly obvious

00:06:49.130 --> 00:06:52.120
in colonial debates
over mixed pulque.

00:06:52.120 --> 00:06:55.450
So, pulque sellers mixed pulque
with all kinds of things,

00:06:55.450 --> 00:06:58.680
with fruit, with meat,
occasionally with peyote

00:06:58.680 --> 00:07:01.370
and with herbs and
different kinds of roots.

00:07:01.370 --> 00:07:04.150
And so for Spanish
officials, pure pulque,

00:07:04.150 --> 00:07:07.580
which they called pulque blanco
or like literally white pulque,

00:07:07.580 --> 00:07:09.740
pulque blanco was tolerable.

00:07:09.740 --> 00:07:12.820
I mean, sort of more or less
tolerable in different times,

00:07:12.820 --> 00:07:14.500
but overall, generally
tolerable.

00:07:14.500 --> 00:07:16.120
But mixing it with
anything made it bad

00:07:16.120 --> 00:07:18.020
in the eyes of Spanish
officials.

00:07:18.020 --> 00:07:21.130
As early as 1529, Spanish
officials prohibited the sale

00:07:21.130 --> 00:07:23.170
of pulque mixed with
any other ingredient

00:07:23.170 --> 00:07:25.990
and this regulation continued
throughout the colonial period.

00:07:25.990 --> 00:07:28.650
So viceregal decrees of 1535,

00:07:28.650 --> 00:07:33.850
1671 and 1792 prohibited
yellow pulque and which--

00:07:33.850 --> 00:07:35.680
and they called yellow
pulque corrupt.

00:07:35.680 --> 00:07:39.270
And they defined this yellow
pulque as having "the root,

00:07:39.270 --> 00:07:42.360
the raiz that strengthens
it, causing drunkenness

00:07:42.360 --> 00:07:45.200
that is dangerous to health
and to good customs and from

00:07:45.200 --> 00:07:47.930
which come the crimes,
sins, and abominations

00:07:47.930 --> 00:07:49.640
that we see continually."

00:07:49.640 --> 00:07:52.250
So these decrees proclaimed

00:07:52.250 --> 00:07:55.180
that public stands must sell
only pulque that was "pure

00:07:55.180 --> 00:07:59.120
and clean" of all confection,
mixture, root or corruption.

00:07:59.120 --> 00:08:00.420
And the root that
they were talking

00:08:00.420 --> 00:08:01.720
about was palo de timbre.

00:08:01.720 --> 00:08:04.260
And this is well
not-- like I googled.

00:08:04.260 --> 00:08:05.900
I googled palo de
timbre and this came

00:08:05.900 --> 00:08:08.900
up on a culinary website.

00:08:08.900 --> 00:08:13.650
So this is a plant that is still
used to speed up fermentation.

00:08:13.650 --> 00:08:16.360
And according to this culinary
website, all different parts

00:08:16.360 --> 00:08:18.540
of it can be used to speed
fermentation, still are used.

00:08:18.540 --> 00:08:20.100
So it could be the leaves,
it could be the branches.

00:08:20.100 --> 00:08:22.310
So I don't know, when they
say raiz or root, I don't know

00:08:22.310 --> 00:08:23.610
if they're really
talking about the root

00:08:23.610 --> 00:08:24.910
or if the branch maybe was used.

00:08:24.910 --> 00:08:26.210
It don't look like a
root, but they're talking

00:08:26.210 --> 00:08:27.510
about this palo de timbre.

00:08:27.510 --> 00:08:30.940
So, palo de timbre was
mentioned in many other texts,

00:08:30.940 --> 00:08:34.600
including the 1681 Recopilación
de leyes de los reinos de

00:08:34.600 --> 00:08:38.240
Indias, the compilation
of the colonial laws.

00:08:38.240 --> 00:08:41.510
And the Recopilación warned
against the damaging effects

00:08:41.510 --> 00:08:44.650
of "introducing ingredients
to pulque that are noxious

00:08:44.650 --> 00:08:48.000
to spiritual and
temporal health".

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:51.170
Legislators describe the
Indian practice of "mixing it

00:08:51.170 --> 00:08:54.390
with certain roots, boiling
water and lime which makes it

00:08:54.390 --> 00:08:55.980
so strong that it makes them,

00:08:55.980 --> 00:08:57.840
indigenous people,
lose their senses".

00:08:57.840 --> 00:09:00.150
Then they went on--
"Then being alienated,

00:09:00.150 --> 00:09:02.050
they commit idolatries,
make ceremonies

00:09:02.050 --> 00:09:03.680
and Gentile sacrifices."

00:09:03.680 --> 00:09:07.260
So it's not just that Spanish
officials tolerated the

00:09:07.260 --> 00:09:09.240
consumption of pure
or white pulque,

00:09:09.240 --> 00:09:11.450
but they actually made money
from its sale, so they had like,

00:09:11.450 --> 00:09:13.030
you know, skin on the game.

00:09:13.030 --> 00:09:16.320
In 1668, the crown established
the asiento de pulque.

00:09:16.320 --> 00:09:19.090
They named an administrator
to collect pulque taxes.

00:09:19.090 --> 00:09:20.670
And then in 1763,

00:09:20.670 --> 00:09:22.560
pulque taxation became
the responsibility

00:09:22.560 --> 00:09:25.520
of the Real Hacienda
or the royal treasury.

00:09:25.520 --> 00:09:27.110
So this seems somewhat
paradoxical.

00:09:27.110 --> 00:09:31.310
So if collecting tax money was
the primary concern of crown

00:09:31.310 --> 00:09:33.260
and viceregal authorities,
why would they ban the sale

00:09:33.260 --> 00:09:35.840
of mixed pulque, from which
they could also make money?

00:09:35.840 --> 00:09:37.800
So it's not surprising
that officials would want

00:09:37.800 --> 00:09:41.250
to prohibit the sale of pulque
with like things like peyote

00:09:41.250 --> 00:09:42.840
or maybe other kinds
of materials

00:09:42.840 --> 00:09:45.360
that had obvious
pharmacological properties.

00:09:45.360 --> 00:09:49.400
And in fact Daniel Nemser, who
has written about these issues

00:09:49.400 --> 00:09:52.400
for the late 17th century,

00:09:52.400 --> 00:09:54.960
has shown that Spaniards
actually thought of pulque

00:09:54.960 --> 00:09:56.760
that had been mixed
with certain materials

00:09:56.760 --> 00:10:00.220
as fundamentally altered and
different from pulque blanco.

00:10:00.220 --> 00:10:01.520
So he quotes a theologian

00:10:01.520 --> 00:10:03.310
as using the term
transubstantiate

00:10:03.310 --> 00:10:04.610
to talk about this.

00:10:04.610 --> 00:10:06.240
So this is a material
that's totally different.

00:10:06.240 --> 00:10:08.390
But we might ask what's the
problem with adding fruit

00:10:08.390 --> 00:10:09.690
or meat or other kind--

00:10:09.690 --> 00:10:11.990
you know, adulterating it
in other kinds of ways.

00:10:11.990 --> 00:10:16.460
So the fact that officials were
not profiting from all pulque

00:10:16.460 --> 00:10:19.000
but were in fact trying to
discourage the consumption

00:10:19.000 --> 00:10:22.140
of some pulque suggest that
pulque regulations have to do

00:10:22.140 --> 00:10:24.700
with concerns that were
not strictly financial.

00:10:24.700 --> 00:10:26.940
So I want to suggest
that the reason

00:10:26.940 --> 00:10:29.280
that Spanish officials
prohibited mixed pulque was

00:10:29.280 --> 00:10:32.050
at least in part because
of its mixed nature.

00:10:32.050 --> 00:10:33.350
So we know very well

00:10:33.350 --> 00:10:35.370
that Spaniards valued
purity of blood.

00:10:35.370 --> 00:10:40.190
So to have high status or
to occupy certain positions,

00:10:40.190 --> 00:10:42.970
you had to prove that you had
limpieza de sangre or, you know,

00:10:42.970 --> 00:10:44.390
translated as purity of blood.

00:10:44.390 --> 00:10:45.710
Meaning, really,
that you could prove

00:10:45.710 --> 00:10:48.210
that you are an old Christian
but it's sort of in--

00:10:48.210 --> 00:10:50.180
in sort of in fact kind of meant

00:10:50.180 --> 00:10:53.080
that you could prove
you're of European descent.

00:10:53.080 --> 00:10:56.830
Presumably, Spaniards also look
for purity in the substances

00:10:56.830 --> 00:10:59.120
that went into physical bodies.

00:10:59.120 --> 00:11:01.830
And so my favorite example
to describe this conjunction

00:11:01.830 --> 00:11:05.200
of ideas about pulque and
ideas about blood lineage comes

00:11:05.200 --> 00:11:08.400
in a set of responses to a
survey of drinking habits

00:11:08.400 --> 00:11:11.830
that the viceregal
government sent out in 1783.

00:11:11.830 --> 00:11:13.940
And so there is a survey, what
do you drink, what's it made

00:11:13.940 --> 00:11:15.240
out of, when do you drink it.

00:11:15.240 --> 00:11:18.600
And so this yielded a great list
of alcoholic drinks, you know,

00:11:18.600 --> 00:11:21.290
saying where these things were
drunk and what went into them

00:11:21.290 --> 00:11:22.590
and this kind of thing.

00:11:22.590 --> 00:11:24.110
And so most of these
recipes were sort

00:11:24.110 --> 00:11:25.550
of neutrally explanatory.

00:11:25.550 --> 00:11:27.710
So, for example, to make a drink
that is called mantequilla,

00:11:27.710 --> 00:11:30.740
which in this period I think
would translate literally

00:11:30.740 --> 00:11:32.040
as lard.

00:11:32.040 --> 00:11:33.340
I don't know why it's
called mantequilla.

00:11:33.340 --> 00:11:35.610
But informants reported that
they "mixed" aguardiente

00:11:35.610 --> 00:11:39.240
or distilled alcohol,
and pulque and sugar

00:11:39.240 --> 00:11:40.540
or some other sweetener.

00:11:40.540 --> 00:11:42.580
So this was a mixture but
this is reported in a sort

00:11:42.580 --> 00:11:44.260
of matter of fact way.

00:11:44.260 --> 00:11:47.880
In this list, a drink
called coyote stands out.

00:11:47.880 --> 00:11:52.370
So, coyote was "composed of
inferior pulque, dark honey

00:11:52.370 --> 00:11:56.270
and palo de timbre," this plant,
"and putting it in an infusion,

00:11:56.270 --> 00:11:58.540
it gets stronger and people
drink it although it's

00:11:58.540 --> 00:11:59.840
very harmful".

00:11:59.840 --> 00:12:01.140
And the term is nocivo.

00:12:01.140 --> 00:12:03.130
The term always-- I
translated it I think as noxious

00:12:03.130 --> 00:12:05.260
at one point and then I
translated it as harmful

00:12:05.260 --> 00:12:07.260
but it's always-- it's
almost always nocivo.

00:12:07.260 --> 00:12:08.560
So that's interesting.

00:12:08.560 --> 00:12:10.470
You know that this word is
like through the century sort

00:12:10.470 --> 00:12:14.020
of repeated in relation to
this mixed, mixed pulque.

00:12:14.020 --> 00:12:15.680
So the name of this
drink, this--

00:12:15.680 --> 00:12:17.470
the name coyote is striking.

00:12:17.470 --> 00:12:19.380
In the eight-- as
you I'm sure know--

00:12:19.380 --> 00:12:21.730
In the 18th century the
term coyote was used

00:12:21.730 --> 00:12:24.830
to describe a person of mixed
descent, theoretically one

00:12:24.830 --> 00:12:29.680
who is three quarters indigenous
and one quarter Spanish.

00:12:29.680 --> 00:12:33.080
So liquid coyote-- and OK, I did
have a slide, I can remember.

00:12:33.080 --> 00:12:35.900
So liquid coyotes and human
coyotes then were both

00:12:35.900 --> 00:12:37.760
characterized by mixture.

00:12:37.760 --> 00:12:41.520
So the description of the
beverage coyote as harmful

00:12:41.520 --> 00:12:44.330
and low grade recall some
contemporary Spanish ideas

00:12:44.330 --> 00:12:46.650
that castas or people of
mixed racial background,

00:12:46.650 --> 00:12:49.570
including so called
coyotes were inferior,

00:12:49.570 --> 00:12:51.120
dangerous and disorderly.

00:12:51.120 --> 00:12:56.190
So in 1763, the Capuchin
chronicler Francisco de Ajofrín

00:12:56.190 --> 00:12:58.980
wrote, "lobos, [inaudible]
and coyotes,"

00:12:58.980 --> 00:13:01.320
these are these categories
of mixed people,

00:13:01.320 --> 00:13:04.410
"are fierce people
of bizarre customs."

00:13:04.410 --> 00:13:07.260
This is not the only kind
of depiction of these castas

00:13:07.260 --> 00:13:08.560
or these mixed people.

00:13:08.560 --> 00:13:10.070
So I brought these
caste paintings

00:13:10.070 --> 00:13:12.600
because they show people
drinking pulque so you can sort

00:13:12.600 --> 00:13:15.760
of see what it might have,
you know, been like in action.

00:13:15.760 --> 00:13:18.920
But you can also see that these
are paintings of mixed people

00:13:18.920 --> 00:13:22.970
but they show the sort of
harmonious family unit.

00:13:22.970 --> 00:13:26.750
And then those of you to whom
I spoke before this know--

00:13:26.750 --> 00:13:28.720
and was like sort of confused
because the caste painting

00:13:28.720 --> 00:13:31.720
that we have on our program
today actually doesn't have

00:13:31.720 --> 00:13:33.020
[inaudible] so I don't
know what that means,

00:13:33.020 --> 00:13:35.200
but we can talk about that.

00:13:35.200 --> 00:13:37.160
So the connection
between lineage--

00:13:37.160 --> 00:13:39.030
sorry, liquids and
lineage is clear

00:13:39.030 --> 00:13:42.670
in the 1611 Spanish dictionary
in which the noun mezcla

00:13:42.670 --> 00:13:46.170
or mixture was defined as
"the incorporation of a liquid

00:13:46.170 --> 00:13:53.140
with another" and its verb form,
this dictionary defined mezclar,

00:13:53.140 --> 00:13:56.830
the verb to mix as meaning
"to unite diverse things".

00:13:56.830 --> 00:14:00.660
And then the example
was "to mix lineages

00:14:00.660 --> 00:14:03.000
when some lineages are mixed
up with others that are not

00:14:03.000 --> 00:14:05.760
of the same calidad or quality".

00:14:05.760 --> 00:14:08.010
The dictionary went on to say--

00:14:08.010 --> 00:14:10.190
and we say it is a thing
without mixture when it's pure.

00:14:10.190 --> 00:14:12.220
So, purity, mixture, process.

00:14:12.220 --> 00:14:15.680
Calidad use-- the word
used in the 1611 dictionary

00:14:15.680 --> 00:14:19.250
in a general way, meaning sort
of quality or type was also used

00:14:19.250 --> 00:14:21.540
to indicate social status
in the colonial period.

00:14:21.540 --> 00:14:25.370
So there are several ways to
approach the Spanish fears

00:14:25.370 --> 00:14:27.340
about these mixed drinks.

00:14:27.340 --> 00:14:29.230
So first, these kind of--

00:14:29.230 --> 00:14:32.710
these rules in legislation
reflect a sort

00:14:32.710 --> 00:14:35.600
of material solution
to fears about mixing.

00:14:35.600 --> 00:14:38.310
So Spanish officials feared
that the mixing of liquids

00:14:38.310 --> 00:14:40.190
and other ingredients
in pulque drinks

00:14:40.190 --> 00:14:43.130
because of resulting inebriation
could lead to the mixing

00:14:43.130 --> 00:14:46.070
of bodies, and ultimately the
mixing of blood, both in terms

00:14:46.070 --> 00:14:48.980
of like the bloodshed
that comes from violence,

00:14:48.980 --> 00:14:52.730
and also the mixing of
lineages that could, you know,

00:14:52.730 --> 00:14:54.530
happen when people had
sex with each other

00:14:54.530 --> 00:14:56.370
and had kids together.

00:14:56.370 --> 00:14:59.420
So possibly through pulque
fuel the sexual relations.

00:14:59.420 --> 00:15:02.320
So we've seen example of
these in the ban of sales

00:15:02.320 --> 00:15:06.400
of all pulque after the 1692
bread riots in Mexico City.

00:15:06.400 --> 00:15:09.120
So in this-- right after
these riots, officials claimed

00:15:09.120 --> 00:15:11.360
that the insurrection had
been planned in pulquerias

00:15:11.360 --> 00:15:12.930
and then they banned
pulque briefly.

00:15:12.930 --> 00:15:14.800
There was like a little bit of
a disagreement between the crown

00:15:14.800 --> 00:15:17.050
and the viceregal government.

00:15:17.050 --> 00:15:19.460
And Daniel Nemser, this person I
have mentioned before has talked

00:15:19.460 --> 00:15:22.450
in at length about this-- he
wrote an article about this.

00:15:22.450 --> 00:15:24.760
He said the study of mixed
pulque offered a lead

00:15:24.760 --> 00:15:28.040
to language for talking
about race mixing, mestizaje,

00:15:28.040 --> 00:15:31.680
while simultaneously
constituting pulque consumers

00:15:31.680 --> 00:15:35.040
as a seditious collective
subject, a plebe defined,

00:15:35.040 --> 00:15:36.410
like pulque, by mixing.

00:15:36.410 --> 00:15:40.580
So he's talking about
this issue in this period.

00:15:40.580 --> 00:15:42.670
So as Nemser's work indicates,

00:15:42.670 --> 00:15:45.520
this worry about mixing pulque
was also a manifestation

00:15:45.520 --> 00:15:47.650
of biopower, biopolitics
in the way

00:15:47.650 --> 00:15:49.500
that Foucault has
talked about it.

00:15:49.500 --> 00:15:51.870
So by claiming to
protect colonial residents

00:15:51.870 --> 00:15:54.130
from the disorderly
effects of mixing pulque,

00:15:54.130 --> 00:15:57.370
the state was trying to control
their bodies and their actions

00:15:57.370 --> 00:15:59.170
and it was then also
another way to sort

00:15:59.170 --> 00:16:02.870
of perpetuate this discourse as
of-- about mixing as undesirable

00:16:02.870 --> 00:16:05.590
and corrupting and bad.

00:16:05.590 --> 00:16:07.220
Spanish officials
were not only worried

00:16:07.220 --> 00:16:09.590
about Spanish identity
being adulterated, however,

00:16:09.590 --> 00:16:10.890
but they were also worried

00:16:10.890 --> 00:16:12.630
about indigenous identity
being adulterated.

00:16:12.630 --> 00:16:14.120
And we see this like
all over the place.

00:16:14.120 --> 00:16:17.470
So we see this in regular
decrees prohibiting Spaniards,

00:16:17.470 --> 00:16:19.510
blacks and castas, mixed people,

00:16:19.510 --> 00:16:20.980
from living in indigenous
villages.

00:16:20.980 --> 00:16:23.090
And we also see this in
the two republic idea,

00:16:23.090 --> 00:16:26.040
the idea that the colonial
world should be split up sort

00:16:26.040 --> 00:16:27.430
of juridically and
also spatially

00:16:27.430 --> 00:16:30.370
into the republica de indios
and the republica de Espanol.

00:16:30.370 --> 00:16:34.330
Although it's like only a
fantasy, it never works.

00:16:34.330 --> 00:16:36.970
So, ideas about pure
Indianness and pure pulque

00:16:36.970 --> 00:16:39.060
and the importance of
maintaining the purity

00:16:39.060 --> 00:16:40.650
of both were linked in crown

00:16:40.650 --> 00:16:42.600
and viceregal policies
limiting the sale

00:16:42.600 --> 00:16:45.920
of the permitted white
pulque to indigenous sellers.

00:16:45.920 --> 00:16:50.840
Decrees from 1608, 1635 and
1639 restricted licenses

00:16:50.840 --> 00:16:54.310
for selling pulque
to indigenous women,

00:16:54.310 --> 00:16:56.180
although in practice
Spaniards, as well as men

00:16:56.180 --> 00:16:57.980
of different groups were
involved in the trade

00:16:57.980 --> 00:17:02.540
in Mexico City certainly by the
18th century or possibly before.

00:17:02.540 --> 00:17:04.420
Religious leaders were
specifically worried

00:17:04.420 --> 00:17:06.750
about Spanish cultural
polluting indigenous people.

00:17:06.750 --> 00:17:08.590
In the mid 16th century,

00:17:08.590 --> 00:17:12.300
the friar Diego Duran condemned
mixed pulque writing "today,

00:17:12.300 --> 00:17:16.090
what is called pulque made by
Spaniards from the black honey

00:17:16.090 --> 00:17:18.990
and water with the root
in it was never known

00:17:18.990 --> 00:17:20.350
to the ancients," meaning sort

00:17:20.350 --> 00:17:22.020
of the Nahua people
before contact.

00:17:22.020 --> 00:17:23.790
He's writing in Central Mexico.

00:17:23.790 --> 00:17:26.100
"Nor do they know how to
concoct it until the blacks

00:17:26.100 --> 00:17:27.940
and Spaniards invented it."

00:17:27.940 --> 00:17:30.570
And so this seems to be
the recipe for coyote

00:17:30.570 --> 00:17:33.850
that we see later, much later,
200 years later in the 179--

00:17:33.850 --> 00:17:37.500
in the 1783 text that
I talked about earlier.

00:17:37.500 --> 00:17:39.740
Duran and-- goes on to
describe white pulque

00:17:39.740 --> 00:17:44.290
as "their own native wine"
which is lighter and medicinal,

00:17:44.290 --> 00:17:46.470
meaning Nahua people's
native wine,

00:17:46.470 --> 00:17:49.700
and then describes this
mixed variant as "diabolical,

00:17:49.700 --> 00:17:53.670
stinking, black, potent, rough,
without flavor or taste".

00:17:53.670 --> 00:17:56.220
So, again, so mixture makes
pulque diabolical while white

00:17:56.220 --> 00:17:59.330
pulque is both purely indigenous
and better and more wholesome

00:17:59.330 --> 00:18:01.940
but also kind of
rooted in the past.

00:18:01.940 --> 00:18:04.540
In the 1634 Nahua to
confession manual,

00:18:04.540 --> 00:18:07.560
Bartolome de Alva addressed
indigenous Mexicans directly.

00:18:07.560 --> 00:18:11.030
I mean, sort of, lamenting
that "for a gourd of pulque,

00:18:11.030 --> 00:18:13.550
or a cup of wine, you
cast your souls to hell

00:18:13.550 --> 00:18:15.720
and give them to the devil."

00:18:15.720 --> 00:18:18.880
And he claimed that before
contact with Spaniards,

00:18:18.880 --> 00:18:22.680
Nahua people, "had
discretion, prudence, fear,

00:18:22.680 --> 00:18:24.710
shame and good breeding,

00:18:24.710 --> 00:18:26.920
but he said that now they
had been turned into beasts

00:18:26.920 --> 00:18:29.540
by drunkenness and
intoxication."

00:18:29.540 --> 00:18:32.430
So he wrote, "even though the
ancients, your elders, drink--

00:18:32.430 --> 00:18:35.590
excuse me, it was with
moderation and restraint

00:18:35.590 --> 00:18:37.740
as your neighbors, the
Spaniards, do today."

00:18:37.740 --> 00:18:39.570
Which I don't really know
what to make of that but--

00:18:39.570 --> 00:18:41.320
And if by some chance
they sometimes they used

00:18:41.320 --> 00:18:42.620
to discover some drunkard,

00:18:42.620 --> 00:18:44.530
they immediately took
away his life for it.

00:18:44.530 --> 00:18:47.320
And now in our times, it exists
because nobody restrains you

00:18:47.320 --> 00:18:48.620
with the death penalty.

00:18:48.620 --> 00:18:50.190
And this is actually in
reference to this idea

00:18:50.190 --> 00:18:53.480
that comes from the Florentine
Codex that under the Aztecs,

00:18:53.480 --> 00:18:55.210
the drinking of pulque
was restricted

00:18:55.210 --> 00:18:59.200
to ritual specialists
and the elderly.

00:18:59.200 --> 00:19:01.420
Although it seems that this
was-- this never really--

00:19:01.420 --> 00:19:03.900
This was not really the
case, but there is this--

00:19:03.900 --> 00:19:06.400
people think that
this is the case.

00:19:06.400 --> 00:19:11.650
So Duran and Alva then
were idealizing the past,

00:19:11.650 --> 00:19:14.820
this Nahua past, and using
pulque as a way to argue

00:19:14.820 --> 00:19:16.310
for the need to protect
but really

00:19:16.310 --> 00:19:18.210
to regulate native bodies.

00:19:18.210 --> 00:19:19.630
Yet in reality, of course,

00:19:19.630 --> 00:19:21.670
people and practices
were actively mixing

00:19:21.670 --> 00:19:23.770
in all kinds of ways.

00:19:23.770 --> 00:19:27.300
Friar Ilarione da Bergamo,
who is an Italian Capuchin

00:19:27.300 --> 00:19:28.630
who dropped-- traveled
in New Spain

00:19:28.630 --> 00:19:31.900
in the 1760s described
maguey in this way.

00:19:31.900 --> 00:19:33.970
So, maguey, the plant, right,
from which pulque comes.

00:19:33.970 --> 00:19:37.500
So he says, as you can read,
this plant is also held

00:19:37.500 --> 00:19:40.190
in special esteem by the
Most Blessed Virgin Mary

00:19:40.190 --> 00:19:42.340
because in the year
1540 she appeared

00:19:42.340 --> 00:19:45.530
to an Indian named Juan
de Aguila on the hill

00:19:45.530 --> 00:19:48.680
of Totoltepec, which is not far
from Mexico City, and told him

00:19:48.680 --> 00:19:51.040
that he should look for her
image in the very same place.

00:19:51.040 --> 00:19:53.140
After initial efforts he
found in the middle of one

00:19:53.140 --> 00:19:55.940
of these plants a small
statute of the Blessed Virgin

00:19:55.940 --> 00:19:58.060
with her babe in her arms
though it's not known

00:19:58.060 --> 00:19:59.710
from what material it is made.

00:19:59.710 --> 00:20:02.160
The Mexicans showed great faith
and devotion to this and in time

00:20:02.160 --> 00:20:04.240
of greatest need they have
a special recourse to it

00:20:04.240 --> 00:20:05.540
through public prayers.

00:20:05.540 --> 00:20:07.160
So what does this sound like?

00:20:07.160 --> 00:20:09.860
It sounds like the Virgin
of Guadalupe, right?

00:20:09.860 --> 00:20:13.120
So the Virgin of Guadalupe just
nine years before had appeared

00:20:13.120 --> 00:20:15.810
to Juan Diego at Tepeyac
and she, you know,

00:20:15.810 --> 00:20:17.110
appears in this hill

00:20:17.110 --> 00:20:20.720
where Tonantzin was
important, this earlier deity.

00:20:20.720 --> 00:20:24.020
This description also calls to
Mayahuel, who is the goddess

00:20:24.020 --> 00:20:28.050
of maguey and pulque depicted
in both the Codex Mendoza

00:20:28.050 --> 00:20:29.870
and then here of an image
from the Codex Borgia,

00:20:29.870 --> 00:20:33.520
as a woman with 400 breasts
nursing a baby while sitting

00:20:33.520 --> 00:20:35.830
in a maguey plant.

00:20:35.830 --> 00:20:40.450
And so, you know, this is how
it's been interpreted, so.

00:20:40.450 --> 00:20:42.760
However, pulque was pragmatic--

00:20:42.760 --> 00:20:44.930
was hybrid in a more
pragmatic way as well.

00:20:44.930 --> 00:20:46.900
So it's hybrid just because
lots of people drink it

00:20:46.900 --> 00:20:48.290
in many different situations.

00:20:48.290 --> 00:20:54.090
So the same Italian friar wrote,
today consumption of pulque is

00:20:54.090 --> 00:20:56.070
so widespread that
everyone drinks it.

00:20:56.070 --> 00:20:57.370
There are public pulquerias,

00:20:57.370 --> 00:20:59.100
which are like our
public wine shops.

00:20:59.100 --> 00:21:01.600
A few years ago, it was not
proper for people with any kind

00:21:01.600 --> 00:21:03.310
of social standing
to go into them

00:21:03.310 --> 00:21:06.020
because entering a place
frequented only by drunks

00:21:06.020 --> 00:21:07.810
and by rabble of
every ilk seemed

00:21:07.810 --> 00:21:09.660
to undercut their
respectability.

00:21:09.660 --> 00:21:11.260
Now, people of every
rank frequent them,

00:21:11.260 --> 00:21:13.470
and during the time
of my stay in Mexico,

00:21:13.470 --> 00:21:16.070
I observed many carriages and
coaches of gentlemen, ladies,

00:21:16.070 --> 00:21:18.500
merchants and other respectable
people heading to these places.

00:21:18.500 --> 00:21:20.300
And this is my favorite part.

00:21:20.300 --> 00:21:22.530
As for myself, in the roughly
five years that I resided

00:21:22.530 --> 00:21:24.890
in that country, I could not
get used to drinking that liquor

00:21:24.890 --> 00:21:26.380
because of its foul odor.

00:21:26.380 --> 00:21:28.010
Even though Europeans,
after drinking it for two

00:21:28.010 --> 00:21:29.930
or three days became
even more keen on it

00:21:29.930 --> 00:21:32.300
than the local population
itself.

00:21:32.300 --> 00:21:34.800
So Bergamo here is obviously
participating in the sort

00:21:34.800 --> 00:21:37.590
of discourse that sees Spanish
creoles as sort of degraded

00:21:37.590 --> 00:21:39.750
because of their
American origins.

00:21:39.750 --> 00:21:42.470
But it's also interesting
because it shows--

00:21:42.470 --> 00:21:45.580
and he's saying in this
period but I think it's true

00:21:45.580 --> 00:21:48.320
or it's definitely true early as
well that pulque consumption was

00:21:48.320 --> 00:21:50.510
of course not only limited
to indigenous people.

00:21:50.510 --> 00:21:52.910
However, much the discourse
about pulque revolved

00:21:52.910 --> 00:21:57.220
around identifying them as
the primary pulque drinkers.

00:21:57.220 --> 00:21:58.520
So ultimately, I'm
interested in the way

00:21:58.520 --> 00:22:00.270
that this colonial
pulque discourse may

00:22:00.270 --> 00:22:02.720
or may not foreshadow
ideas about indigeneity

00:22:02.720 --> 00:22:06.680
and Mexican identity in the
19th, 20th, and 21st centuries.

00:22:06.680 --> 00:22:10.450
So after 21-- I'm sorry,
after 1821, caste distinctions

00:22:10.450 --> 00:22:13.840
and ethnic privileges and
protections were abolished

00:22:13.840 --> 00:22:15.550
by liberal policymakers.

00:22:15.550 --> 00:22:18.520
After 1910, mixture
was celebrated.

00:22:18.520 --> 00:22:19.860
The idea the Indian as part

00:22:19.860 --> 00:22:21.740
of the cosmic race
really became a linchpin

00:22:21.740 --> 00:22:24.850
for Mexican national
identity and the idea here was

00:22:24.850 --> 00:22:26.150
that the Indian was part

00:22:26.150 --> 00:22:28.260
of the past while the
mestiza was the future.

00:22:28.260 --> 00:22:29.890
And I should say going
back to the 19th century,

00:22:29.890 --> 00:22:31.740
Deborah Toner has written
this wonderful book,

00:22:31.740 --> 00:22:33.970
which I can't remember
the name of,

00:22:33.970 --> 00:22:38.020
but about the representations
of alcohol and drunkenness

00:22:38.020 --> 00:22:40.130
and the relationship to national
identity in the 19th century.

00:22:40.130 --> 00:22:43.410
So that's very good book.

00:22:43.410 --> 00:22:45.760
But so the modern-- In
the modernization products

00:22:45.760 --> 00:22:48.290
of the early to mid
20th century,

00:22:48.290 --> 00:22:49.590
pulque sort of fell behind.

00:22:49.590 --> 00:22:52.330
So the state actually
encourages beer consumption

00:22:52.330 --> 00:22:54.420
over pulque consumption.

00:22:54.420 --> 00:22:55.890
Beer was taxed less heavily.

00:22:55.890 --> 00:22:58.280
There weren't as many
hygienic regulations.

00:22:58.280 --> 00:23:01.740
The state was subsidizing
some of the beer producers.

00:23:01.740 --> 00:23:04.660
And in part, this is because
it's seen as sort of modern

00:23:04.660 --> 00:23:08.080
and progressive and clean,
and pulque is characterized

00:23:08.080 --> 00:23:10.140
as not clean in this period.

00:23:10.140 --> 00:23:12.780
Now in the 21st century,
pulque is having a resurgence

00:23:12.780 --> 00:23:15.510
as middleclass students and all
kinds of people go to pulquerias

00:23:15.510 --> 00:23:16.900
and it's very, very hip.

00:23:16.900 --> 00:23:18.690
That's the word that-- and so
it was used to describe it.

00:23:18.690 --> 00:23:21.240
So the New York Times and the
LA Times have had articles

00:23:21.240 --> 00:23:25.010
in their travel sections within
the past five years or so

00:23:25.010 --> 00:23:26.310
which emphasize how
pulque is sort

00:23:26.310 --> 00:23:28.000
of the symbol of Mexicanness.

00:23:28.000 --> 00:23:30.370
So much of the current
pulque discourse revolves

00:23:30.370 --> 00:23:33.480
around defining Mexico through
a purely indigenous past.

00:23:33.480 --> 00:23:36.320
And so here we have
again Pulque La Lucha.

00:23:36.320 --> 00:23:39.390
This is advertised, as you
can see it down there in that

00:23:39.390 --> 00:23:42.580
like ribbon on the bottom, it
says it's older than tequila,

00:23:42.580 --> 00:23:45.060
stronger than beer, it's the
original drink of Mexico.

00:23:45.060 --> 00:23:48.080
And the website go-- It
claims that the drink

00:23:48.080 --> 00:23:50.380
"survived the ravages
of the European invaders

00:23:50.380 --> 00:23:52.610
for three centuries
prior to the formation

00:23:52.610 --> 00:23:53.910
of the Republic of Mexico."

00:23:53.910 --> 00:23:56.200
And I guess none of these
things are really not--

00:23:56.200 --> 00:23:57.590
are untrue, you know, but it--

00:23:57.590 --> 00:23:59.100
but it's sort of the
way they're using it

00:23:59.100 --> 00:24:00.400
to advertise, it's interesting.

00:24:00.400 --> 00:24:01.950
The New York Times
describes pulque

00:24:01.950 --> 00:24:04.360
in one these travel
articles, it's "a thick

00:24:04.360 --> 00:24:06.470
and pungent 2000 year
old Aztec drink."

00:24:06.470 --> 00:24:08.590
We know the Aztecs were
not 2000 years old.

00:24:08.590 --> 00:24:10.940
And "a toast to the Aztec gods."

00:24:10.940 --> 00:24:13.340
So I'll end by saying
that it's tempting

00:24:13.340 --> 00:24:16.180
to see historical continuities
between the colonial

00:24:16.180 --> 00:24:19.080
and modern idealizations
of indigenous identity

00:24:19.080 --> 00:24:21.500
and the effort to
discursively define Indians

00:24:21.500 --> 00:24:22.870
as pure in both cases.

00:24:22.870 --> 00:24:25.500
And that was really where
my emphasis lay, I think,

00:24:25.500 --> 00:24:27.490
when I first started
thinking about this.

00:24:27.490 --> 00:24:30.070
But when we examine this more
closely, we see a rupture

00:24:30.070 --> 00:24:31.870
with the colonial past as well.

00:24:31.870 --> 00:24:34.700
Today's pulque discourse
emphasizes the mixed nature

00:24:34.700 --> 00:24:37.770
of Mexican identity and in many
ways relegates its indigenous

00:24:37.770 --> 00:24:39.650
identity to the past.

00:24:39.650 --> 00:24:40.950
However, throughout
the colonial period,

00:24:40.950 --> 00:24:42.560
indigenous people
were a central concern

00:24:42.560 --> 00:24:45.330
of the Spanish colonial
authorities and one of the ways

00:24:45.330 --> 00:24:46.630
that Spanish authorities try

00:24:46.630 --> 00:24:48.490
to contain indigenous
people and their economics.

00:24:48.490 --> 00:24:51.140
Sorry, and their economic
activities was specifically

00:24:51.140 --> 00:24:53.880
through this pulque discourse.

00:24:53.880 --> 00:24:55.680
Thank you.

00:24:55.680 --> 00:25:00.500
[ Applause ]

