00:26:26.070 --> 00:26:28.370
Religiously Appropriating
Indios:

00:26:28.370 --> 00:26:31.210
20th- and 16th-Century
Theological Production from

00:26:31.210 --> 00:26:34.230
and by...well, Indios.

00:26:39.870 --> 00:26:41.170
&gt;&gt; Garry Sparks: Great.

00:26:41.170 --> 00:26:42.470
Many thanks.

00:26:42.470 --> 00:26:43.770
The title is supposed to be
somewhat of a double entendre

00:26:43.770 --> 00:26:47.790
which I hope will become a
little more clear as we proceed.

00:26:47.790 --> 00:26:50.680
And if you had never heard of
the Theologia Indorum before

00:26:50.680 --> 00:26:56.130
in Ralph's nice introduction,
I'll unpack that as well.

00:26:56.130 --> 00:27:04.460
Based on the use of the term,
since at least the medieval era

00:27:04.460 --> 00:27:08.070
and the application or perhaps
better said, the misapplication

00:27:08.070 --> 00:27:12.230
of Indorum to the Americas,
it served as a catchall phrase

00:27:12.230 --> 00:27:15.680
for all fantastic objects
from an exotic land,

00:27:15.680 --> 00:27:19.370
namely its flora, fauna and
peoples, and by extension,

00:27:19.370 --> 00:27:22.630
their rights, customs and laws.

00:27:22.630 --> 00:27:24.910
Accompanied with the
emergence of the Spanish Empire

00:27:24.910 --> 00:27:28.480
and its ideology of clean
or pure blood, the category

00:27:28.480 --> 00:27:32.250
of Indio was further relegated
to a pejorative status socially,

00:27:32.250 --> 00:27:34.830
politically, as well
as theologically.

00:27:34.830 --> 00:27:37.900
And much of the history is
own religion in Latin America

00:27:37.900 --> 00:27:41.550
by focusing on records of
the out of the phase tale

00:27:41.550 --> 00:27:44.530
of early missionaries'
preoccupation for the endurance

00:27:44.530 --> 00:27:48.920
of indigenous religions as
forms of idolatry, witchcraft

00:27:48.920 --> 00:27:52.560
or heresy, especially when
seen as mixed with Christianity

00:27:52.560 --> 00:27:56.730
and thus akin to a
spiritual mysticism.

00:27:56.730 --> 00:28:00.350
As a result, many cultural
theories even those sympathetic

00:28:00.350 --> 00:28:03.130
to native peoples like
postcolonialism tend

00:28:03.130 --> 00:28:07.370
to relegate indigenous people to
the options of a simple binary,

00:28:07.370 --> 00:28:11.020
of only being either
overly-romanticized reactionary

00:28:11.020 --> 00:28:13.950
resistors or passive victims

00:28:13.950 --> 00:28:17.170
who are simply coerced
into a new religion.

00:28:17.170 --> 00:28:20.070
Thus ironically such
binary options limit

00:28:20.070 --> 00:28:24.150
and undervalue the agency and
reasoning of indigenous peoples,

00:28:24.150 --> 00:28:27.260
both historically and presently.

00:28:27.260 --> 00:28:30.440
And yet on the other hand,
the early paper trail written

00:28:30.440 --> 00:28:33.080
in indigenous languages
by both missionaries

00:28:33.080 --> 00:28:37.950
and early indigenous
peoples also drew from--

00:28:37.950 --> 00:28:42.010
oh, excuse me, evinces a
more complex engagement

00:28:42.010 --> 00:28:45.530
of where native peoples and
mendicant missionaries also drew

00:28:45.530 --> 00:28:49.220
from the world views of the
proverbial other to reconfigure,

00:28:49.220 --> 00:28:53.260
if not also translate
and maintain their own.

00:28:53.260 --> 00:28:56.460
Now among the earliest of these
documents of course written

00:28:56.460 --> 00:28:59.210
by the Highland Maya
in particular

00:28:59.210 --> 00:29:02.620
in Quechan languages is
the Popol Vuh which serves

00:29:02.620 --> 00:29:06.220
for Mayanists and indigenous
activists as a cornerstone

00:29:06.220 --> 00:29:10.280
within a larger body of early
Native American literature.

00:29:10.280 --> 00:29:11.580
However, the references

00:29:11.580 --> 00:29:14.890
to Christianity have remained
a perennial puzzle leading some

00:29:14.890 --> 00:29:18.890
scholars to argue that the Maya
authors were resisting either

00:29:18.890 --> 00:29:22.660
Spanish Christendom at large
or the specific practices

00:29:22.660 --> 00:29:25.160
of missionaries in
general, such as preaching

00:29:25.160 --> 00:29:26.950
or doctrinal teaching.

00:29:26.950 --> 00:29:30.020
And most of this confusion
lies in the opening lines.

00:29:30.020 --> 00:29:31.730
The dates of the Popol Vuh
if you're not familiar,

00:29:31.730 --> 00:29:34.800
redaction dates are
1554 to 1558.

00:29:34.800 --> 00:29:38.460
And the first line of the Popol
Vuh, the K'iche' authors state

00:29:38.460 --> 00:29:40.250
that their text is "the root

00:29:40.250 --> 00:29:42.960
of the ancient word",
the ojer tzij.

00:29:42.960 --> 00:29:46.670
Only to then juxtapose
their ancient word

00:29:46.670 --> 00:29:49.770
with what they refer to a
few lines later as the talk

00:29:49.770 --> 00:29:52.540
about god, uch'ab'al Dios.

00:29:52.540 --> 00:29:56.080
In this way, the K'iche'
authors used Christianity

00:29:56.080 --> 00:30:01.140
and the missionaries "talk about
god" as a foil against which

00:30:01.140 --> 00:30:06.260
to reassert a pre-contact
Maya cosmology.

00:30:06.260 --> 00:30:09.950
However, the specific phrase
uch'ab'al Dios was not coined

00:30:09.950 --> 00:30:12.880
by the K'iche redactors
of the Popol Vuh,

00:30:12.880 --> 00:30:15.430
but rather they lifted it
from among the writings

00:30:15.430 --> 00:30:19.070
of a Dominican friar,
specifically Domingo de Vico.

00:30:19.070 --> 00:30:22.520
In other words, rather than
merely referring to Christianity

00:30:22.520 --> 00:30:25.910
in general in this opening
preamble of the Popol Vuh,

00:30:25.910 --> 00:30:28.850
by this phrase the authors
of the Popol Vuh indicate

00:30:28.850 --> 00:30:31.370
that they have read and
are responding directly

00:30:31.370 --> 00:30:34.760
to the first theology
written in the Americas,

00:30:34.760 --> 00:30:37.500
Vico's Theologia Indorum.

00:30:37.500 --> 00:30:40.110
Of the early mendicant
missionaries,

00:30:40.110 --> 00:30:42.900
Domingo de Vico compiled
the first important works

00:30:42.900 --> 00:30:46.500
on numerous Mayan languages
after arriving into the Americas

00:30:46.500 --> 00:30:50.600
in 1544 with over 40 other
Dominican missionaries

00:30:50.600 --> 00:30:53.030
and Bartolome de las Casas.

00:30:53.030 --> 00:30:56.040
Within a short time, Vico is
said to have learned no less

00:30:56.040 --> 00:30:59.180
than seven different
Mayan languages.

00:30:59.180 --> 00:31:02.730
And one year prior to
his death, in 1555,

00:31:02.730 --> 00:31:04.990
he completed his
Theologia Indorum,

00:31:04.990 --> 00:31:09.930
a theology for the Indians
or theology of the Indians.

00:31:09.930 --> 00:31:13.580
Consisting of almost
1000 manuscript pages,

00:31:13.580 --> 00:31:19.170
divided into 218 chapters
across two distinct volumes,

00:31:19.170 --> 00:31:22.190
Vico's Theologia Indorum
addresses a variety

00:31:22.190 --> 00:31:26.250
of theological, moral
and cultural issues.

00:31:26.250 --> 00:31:27.800
And while no first generation

00:31:27.800 --> 00:31:30.140
or even complete
manuscript has survived,

00:31:30.140 --> 00:31:34.040
a positively identified
a now 17 partial versions

00:31:34.040 --> 00:31:36.760
in at least three, if not
five different Highland Maya

00:31:36.760 --> 00:31:38.250
languages which allow

00:31:38.250 --> 00:31:41.020
for a complete reconstruction
of the full text.

00:31:41.020 --> 00:31:44.950
This is simply a chart of the
size of those manuscripts,

00:31:44.950 --> 00:31:46.530
so more or less, where
they reside mostly

00:31:46.530 --> 00:31:48.870
in Paris and Princeton.

00:31:48.870 --> 00:31:52.310
As one of the first generations
of Spanish students to study

00:31:52.310 --> 00:31:55.440
at the University of Salamanca
after the arrival or return

00:31:55.440 --> 00:31:57.970
of Francisco de Vitoria
and the establishment

00:31:57.970 --> 00:32:00.760
of domestic scholasticism
alongside humanism

00:32:00.760 --> 00:32:02.470
as the curricular standard,

00:32:02.470 --> 00:32:05.140
Aquinas's Summa Theologiae
serves

00:32:05.140 --> 00:32:07.410
as both the general
organizing structure

00:32:07.410 --> 00:32:11.210
of Vico's Theologia Indorum
but also the analogical method

00:32:11.210 --> 00:32:14.570
by which Vico strove to
reconcile Catholicism

00:32:14.570 --> 00:32:18.790
with the Maya world view, much
like Aquinas had centuries prior

00:32:18.790 --> 00:32:22.030
but with the Jewish and
Muslim Aristotelianism.

00:32:22.030 --> 00:32:25.100
In this compendium
genre of Summa,

00:32:25.100 --> 00:32:28.270
Vico presented narrative
summaries of biblical characters

00:32:28.270 --> 00:32:31.340
in a stylic and to the
hagiographic stories

00:32:31.340 --> 00:32:33.970
of the popular Golden Legend.

00:32:33.970 --> 00:32:38.670
For example, volume 1 which
Vico finished in 1553 begins

00:32:38.670 --> 00:32:42.970
with the domestic themes of
the names and being of god,

00:32:42.970 --> 00:32:44.860
and continues with
stories and lessons

00:32:44.860 --> 00:32:48.020
of the Catholic Old Testament
while integrating elements

00:32:48.020 --> 00:32:50.990
of Highland Maya
religious material.

00:32:50.990 --> 00:32:54.830
The second volume, finished in
early 1554, presents narratives

00:32:54.830 --> 00:32:57.990
of the New Testament and
incorporates standard

00:32:57.990 --> 00:32:59.290
but much more detailed

00:32:59.290 --> 00:33:01.550
than usual catechism material
particularly at a time

00:33:01.550 --> 00:33:04.380
when catechisms were
becoming much more simplistic

00:33:04.380 --> 00:33:06.360
because indigenous
peoples were deemed

00:33:06.360 --> 00:33:08.760
as rudimentary [inaudible],
who just needed

00:33:08.760 --> 00:33:13.700
to memorize their rudimentary
material of doctrine.

00:33:13.700 --> 00:33:15.970
In contrast, the
contemporaneous mendicant--

00:33:15.970 --> 00:33:18.510
to other contemporaneous
mendicant text,

00:33:18.510 --> 00:33:22.580
Vico's Theologia Indorum
distinguishes itself

00:33:22.580 --> 00:33:24.670
in four important ways.

00:33:24.670 --> 00:33:27.810
First, Vico's theology
is not a translation

00:33:27.810 --> 00:33:30.430
of a previously written
work elaborated in Europe

00:33:30.430 --> 00:33:32.920
and then exported and
translated into Mesoamerica

00:33:32.920 --> 00:33:36.190
but rather explicitly
references Maya rituals

00:33:36.190 --> 00:33:39.870
and narratives based on his
own direct conversation with

00:33:39.870 --> 00:33:42.930
and ethnographic
study among the Maya.

00:33:42.930 --> 00:33:46.040
Secondly, the Theologia Indorum
is never in fact ever written,

00:33:46.040 --> 00:33:49.230
let alone translated into
Latin or Castilian Spanish,

00:33:49.230 --> 00:33:52.430
what was originally
composed in K'iche.

00:33:52.430 --> 00:33:55.900
Thirdly, the Theologia Indorum
is the first known work written

00:33:55.900 --> 00:33:58.100
in either North or South America

00:33:58.100 --> 00:34:01.320
to explicitly declare
itself a theology,

00:34:01.320 --> 00:34:04.430
thus intentionally
distinguishing itself in terms

00:34:04.430 --> 00:34:07.020
of genre from its textual peers.

00:34:07.020 --> 00:34:09.690
And finally, I think
perhaps most importantly,

00:34:09.690 --> 00:34:12.820
while apparently commissioned
as an aid for priests,

00:34:12.820 --> 00:34:14.880
the primary readers
directly addressed

00:34:14.880 --> 00:34:19.440
in Vico's texts are not fellow
clergy but rather literate Maya

00:34:19.440 --> 00:34:24.680
to whom he refers as ix, you
all and numi'al, nuk'ajol,

00:34:24.680 --> 00:34:26.800
my daughters and my sons,

00:34:26.800 --> 00:34:29.010
by which the Theologia
Indorum then emerges

00:34:29.010 --> 00:34:32.240
as a direct Christian
reply to the Maya

00:34:32.240 --> 00:34:34.570
and their cosmogonic
narratives found

00:34:34.570 --> 00:34:37.320
in text like the Popol Vuh.

00:34:37.320 --> 00:34:40.420
Now while Vico's obvious aim
pertains to the conversion

00:34:40.420 --> 00:34:42.460
of the Maya to Catholicism,

00:34:42.460 --> 00:34:44.680
his strategy builds
off an affirmation

00:34:44.680 --> 00:34:47.090
of pre-Hispanic Mayan religion.

00:34:47.090 --> 00:34:50.810
In Chapter 25, he argued
against the autonomous mixing

00:34:50.810 --> 00:34:54.300
of Mayan religious practices
with Catholic devotionalism.

00:34:54.300 --> 00:34:57.180
But it does not rule
out altogether a mixing

00:34:57.180 --> 00:35:00.720
of Catholic theology and
indigenous devotional practices.

00:35:00.720 --> 00:35:04.390
Furthermore, he wrote not
only in the K'iche languages

00:35:04.390 --> 00:35:05.920
in which he makes his argument

00:35:05.920 --> 00:35:08.670
and assumes a literate
Maya readership

00:35:08.670 --> 00:35:10.620
but also used the high register

00:35:10.620 --> 00:35:13.340
of Maya ceremonial
discourse typified

00:35:13.340 --> 00:35:17.190
by elaborate poetic parallelisms
and archaic turns of phrases

00:35:17.190 --> 00:35:19.910
which are traceable to
ancient glyphic text.

00:35:19.910 --> 00:35:22.920
A common example of
this is the phrase,

00:35:22.920 --> 00:35:24.800
[inaudible] which means
literally, yellowness,

00:35:24.800 --> 00:35:27.050
greenness, but it is
more or less a couplet

00:35:27.050 --> 00:35:28.810
or lexical parallelism
for wealth,

00:35:28.810 --> 00:35:31.080
and we find this actually
in the hieroglyphic text

00:35:31.080 --> 00:35:32.890
of the classic period.

00:35:32.890 --> 00:35:36.640
Just as notably, Vico
selected motifs and phrases

00:35:36.640 --> 00:35:40.600
from Maya theogony also
found in the Popol Vuh.

00:35:40.600 --> 00:35:43.490
He chose the Maya term for
the other world Xibalba

00:35:43.490 --> 00:35:46.830
that mean hell, and he employed
a Mayan metaphorical language

00:35:46.830 --> 00:35:48.990
of weaving and sewing that
we see in the beginning

00:35:48.990 --> 00:35:52.270
of the Popol Vuh for his
narrative of cosmogenesis rather

00:35:52.270 --> 00:35:56.130
than say, use that
of the biblical book

00:35:56.130 --> 00:35:57.830
which is more language
of pottery

00:35:57.830 --> 00:36:01.080
and smith making--
metalsmithing.

00:36:01.080 --> 00:36:04.810
And he selected terms for his
god, like Tz'aqol, B'itol,

00:36:04.810 --> 00:36:08.470
the Maker and the Modeler and
Alom, K'ajolom, the Bearer

00:36:08.470 --> 00:36:11.540
and the Begetter over
other phrases also found

00:36:11.540 --> 00:36:14.320
in Maya theogony such as
the Sovereign Plumed Serpent

00:36:14.320 --> 00:36:16.800
or Heart of Earth, Heart of Sky.

00:36:16.800 --> 00:36:19.630
And he even refers to his
Christian god explicitly

00:36:19.630 --> 00:36:23.580
as qachuch qaqajaw, our
mother and our father,

00:36:23.580 --> 00:36:26.700
thus modifying the
doctrine of god, the father,

00:36:26.700 --> 00:36:30.780
as the first person or
persona of the triune deity.

00:36:30.780 --> 00:36:32.700
Now, in addition
to the Popol Vuh,

00:36:32.700 --> 00:36:36.780
beginning in the early
1550s, most certainly 1552,

00:36:36.780 --> 00:36:39.600
Highland Maya began to write
numerous other documents

00:36:39.600 --> 00:36:41.770
in their own languages
and exclusively

00:36:41.770 --> 00:36:43.070
for their own purposes.

00:36:43.070 --> 00:36:44.440
They're not for the crown,
not for the audience.

00:36:44.440 --> 00:36:47.820
They are not under
editorial control of clergy.

00:36:47.820 --> 00:36:50.460
But in the mendicant
script or alphabet

00:36:50.460 --> 00:36:53.700
and employing the
Iberian legal genres,

00:36:53.700 --> 00:36:55.790
many of which show
further influence

00:36:55.790 --> 00:36:59.410
of both the Theologia
Indorum and the Popol Vuh.

00:36:59.410 --> 00:37:02.370
The Title of Totonicapan
is arguably the third most

00:37:02.370 --> 00:37:04.120
important K'ichean text.

00:37:04.120 --> 00:37:08.480
And the first seven folios, 14
pages, consist of a redaction

00:37:08.480 --> 00:37:11.370
of key chapters directly
from the first volume

00:37:11.370 --> 00:37:14.100
of the Theologia
Indorum and even list

00:37:14.100 --> 00:37:18.150
and cites the specific
chapter numbers used beginning

00:37:18.150 --> 00:37:20.560
with Chapter 30 and
the story of Genesis

00:37:20.560 --> 00:37:23.350
in the opening line
of this [inaudible].

00:37:23.350 --> 00:37:26.590
However, within their
autonomous appropriation

00:37:26.590 --> 00:37:28.000
of the Theologia Indorum,

00:37:28.000 --> 00:37:30.460
the Title of Totonicapan
further contextualized

00:37:30.460 --> 00:37:33.900
or corrected Vico's
theology by, for example,

00:37:33.900 --> 00:37:35.810
specifying that Cain was killed

00:37:35.810 --> 00:37:38.000
in his [inaudible],
his [inaudible].

00:37:38.000 --> 00:37:41.280
And that Moses confronts a
burning Boysenberry Bush,

00:37:41.280 --> 00:37:43.330
a toucan, a boundary--
a shrub that's used

00:37:43.330 --> 00:37:46.210
as a boundary marker even to
this day among Highland Maya

00:37:46.210 --> 00:37:48.390
to distinguish property lines.

00:37:48.390 --> 00:37:51.480
Details not in the
Theologia Indorum.

00:37:51.480 --> 00:37:55.090
Furthermore, by the eight folio
of the Title of Totonicapan,

00:37:55.090 --> 00:37:59.440
the authors of that text begin
to integrate myths also found

00:37:59.440 --> 00:38:00.960
in the Popol Vuh as if

00:38:00.960 --> 00:38:04.300
to reconcile the pre-Hispanic
Maya religious narratives

00:38:04.300 --> 00:38:08.250
with the biblical material
presented by Vico and equating,

00:38:08.250 --> 00:38:12.150
for example, the mythical
Mesoamerican city of Tolan

00:38:12.150 --> 00:38:15.540
with the biblical
city of Babylon.

00:38:15.540 --> 00:38:20.820
Now curiously in contrast with
earlier K'iche writings of 1554,

00:38:20.820 --> 00:38:23.940
like the Popol Vuh and
the Title of Totonicapan

00:38:23.940 --> 00:38:27.520
which dates most certainly
to 1554, that is to say both

00:38:27.520 --> 00:38:29.080
of these texts are
written one year

00:38:29.080 --> 00:38:31.190
after Vico finished
the first volume

00:38:31.190 --> 00:38:34.090
of his Theologia
Indorum in 1553.

00:38:34.090 --> 00:38:37.520
Later independent K'iche
writings actually mentioned Vico

00:38:37.520 --> 00:38:39.760
and his Theologia by name.

00:38:39.760 --> 00:38:41.940
For example, the third
title of the [inaudible]

00:38:41.940 --> 00:38:44.890
which states the
1598 also argues

00:38:44.890 --> 00:38:48.600
that the legendary mythological
Maya ancestors made of maize

00:38:48.600 --> 00:38:50.520
by the divine grandmother,
Xmukane,

00:38:50.520 --> 00:38:53.590
according to the Popol
Vuh, are direct descendants

00:38:53.590 --> 00:38:55.310
of the prophets and
the patriarchs listed

00:38:55.310 --> 00:38:57.720
in the Catholic Old
Testament as the Title

00:38:57.720 --> 00:38:59.530
of the Totonicapan did.

00:38:59.530 --> 00:39:03.410
Thus via this supposed land
deed, the K'iche Maya argued

00:39:03.410 --> 00:39:06.360
for the validity of their
pre-Hispanic religious

00:39:06.360 --> 00:39:09.590
narratives, ritual
practices and authority

00:39:09.590 --> 00:39:12.800
by not resisting Hispanic
Catholicism like the authors

00:39:12.800 --> 00:39:16.670
of the Popol Vuh did but
rather by grafting onto it.

00:39:16.670 --> 00:39:19.230
Furthermore, this
[inaudible] explicitly cites,

00:39:19.230 --> 00:39:21.630
if you notice the last
line, it's cited there,

00:39:21.630 --> 00:39:27.450
Vico's Theologia Indorum as its
source, which you didn't see

00:39:27.450 --> 00:39:34.050
because I didn't advance
the slide, case in point.

00:39:34.050 --> 00:39:36.880
Now, unfortunately the
Highland Maya paper trail thins

00:39:36.880 --> 00:39:38.830
out after the 1600s.

00:39:38.830 --> 00:39:41.330
And while there is no
evidence that clergy outside

00:39:41.330 --> 00:39:44.130
of the Guatemala Highlands, say
other Dominicans further North

00:39:44.130 --> 00:39:48.700
in Oaxaca, were ever aware of
Vico's theology even there.

00:39:48.700 --> 00:39:51.820
Local references [inaudible]
Guatemala and his work

00:39:51.820 --> 00:39:57.190
in ecclesial accounts seem to
peer out by the 19th century.

00:39:57.190 --> 00:40:02.600
However, as recently as-- by
the mid 1960s, both Catholic

00:40:02.600 --> 00:40:05.780
and Protestant clergy
concerned with social issues,

00:40:05.780 --> 00:40:07.810
issues of social
justice and areas

00:40:07.810 --> 00:40:09.980
with predominantly
indigenous populations,

00:40:09.980 --> 00:40:12.890
like Southern Mexico and
the Andean region began

00:40:12.890 --> 00:40:17.310
to reevaluate the role and value
of culture in large part due

00:40:17.310 --> 00:40:20.300
to the influence of
indigenous activists.

00:40:20.300 --> 00:40:23.620
While clergy and theologians,
such as some Dominicans, Jesuits

00:40:23.620 --> 00:40:26.370
and Maryknolls but also some
Presbyterians, Methodists

00:40:26.370 --> 00:40:29.250
and Lutherans began
to elaborate a--

00:40:29.250 --> 00:40:30.550
what's called the theology

00:40:30.550 --> 00:40:33.140
of enculturation
alongside the theology

00:40:33.140 --> 00:40:34.920
of liberation even prior

00:40:34.920 --> 00:40:37.750
to the second Vatican
council in the 1960s.

00:40:37.750 --> 00:40:40.310
By the 1970s, indigenous
activists

00:40:40.310 --> 00:40:42.590
within various Christian
denominations began

00:40:42.590 --> 00:40:45.350
to produce their own
strands of enculturated

00:40:45.350 --> 00:40:48.530
or indigenized Christian
theology

00:40:48.530 --> 00:40:51.450
through various international,
regional

00:40:51.450 --> 00:40:53.690
and highly local workshops aided

00:40:53.690 --> 00:40:56.340
by sympathetic clergy
and bishops often.

00:40:56.340 --> 00:40:59.390
Indigenous activists helped to
establish an informal network

00:40:59.390 --> 00:41:03.120
of centers, curricula and
publications that argue for ways

00:41:03.120 --> 00:41:06.960
that indigenous religious world
views can constructively engage

00:41:06.960 --> 00:41:09.120
Christian thought and practice.

00:41:09.120 --> 00:41:11.370
For example, for various
Highland Maya of Chiapas

00:41:11.370 --> 00:41:14.960
and Guatemala, the wives of
Mayan men ordained as deacons

00:41:14.960 --> 00:41:19.250
in the Catholic Church also
serve as unofficial deaconesses

00:41:19.250 --> 00:41:21.370
in accord with the
cosmogonic principle

00:41:21.370 --> 00:41:22.710
of gender complementarity.

00:41:22.710 --> 00:41:25.260
I should be very delicate
on this matter because it--

00:41:25.260 --> 00:41:27.650
there was an incidence
that was investigated

00:41:27.650 --> 00:41:30.940
by then Cardinal Joseph
Ratzinger in the diocese

00:41:30.940 --> 00:41:34.110
of San Cristobal de las Casas.

00:41:34.110 --> 00:41:38.020
Just-- This is public,
it didn't happen.

00:41:38.020 --> 00:41:39.890
The-- And the liturgical

00:41:39.890 --> 00:41:42.590
and hagiographic church
calendars are integrated

00:41:42.590 --> 00:41:45.700
in many parishes with
the 260 day Mesoamerican

00:41:45.700 --> 00:41:47.120
ritual calendar.

00:41:47.120 --> 00:41:50.960
Clergy, in many cases Jesuits,
often don't wear habits

00:41:50.960 --> 00:41:53.370
or even the Roman color
but rather the attire

00:41:53.370 --> 00:41:55.780
of traditional Maya
elders in villages.

00:41:55.780 --> 00:41:58.810
The Eucharist I've seen
celebrated on a platter

00:41:58.810 --> 00:42:01.590
or patent in the shape
of the back of a turtle,

00:42:01.590 --> 00:42:03.740
therefore referencing the
fertile surface of the Earth

00:42:03.740 --> 00:42:07.500
as well as the constellation
belt of Orion from which Hunahpu

00:42:07.500 --> 00:42:10.610
and Xbalanque emerged with
the resurrected father

00:42:10.610 --> 00:42:12.520
as the god of maize.

00:42:12.520 --> 00:42:16.590
And in certain services
scripture readings are often

00:42:16.590 --> 00:42:18.360
paired with or accompanied
by readings

00:42:18.360 --> 00:42:22.730
from the Popol Vuh translated
into other local Mayan languages

00:42:22.730 --> 00:42:27.110
such as Tzotzil, Tzeltal and
Q'anjo'bal, thus aligning the

00:42:27.110 --> 00:42:32.250
"word of the lord" with the
Maya ancient word, ojer tzij.

00:42:32.250 --> 00:42:34.190
As a liberation, this
theological movement,

00:42:34.190 --> 00:42:37.660
but in the hands of modern
indigenous intellectuals,

00:42:37.660 --> 00:42:40.430
they struggled for a name
that would not separate them

00:42:40.430 --> 00:42:42.580
from the class analysis
of liberation theology

00:42:42.580 --> 00:42:46.190
or the cultural attentiveness
of enculturation theology,

00:42:46.190 --> 00:42:48.520
but simultaneously
would indicate

00:42:48.520 --> 00:42:51.840
that their approach was
distinctively indigenous

00:42:51.840 --> 00:42:55.210
and one shared in common
across the Americas,

00:42:55.210 --> 00:42:58.080
across distinct indigenous
languages, world views

00:42:58.080 --> 00:42:59.580
and even national histories

00:42:59.580 --> 00:43:03.370
of oppression unique
to native peoples.

00:43:03.370 --> 00:43:06.030
In the end, the term that they
thought best indicated their

00:43:06.030 --> 00:43:08.850
unique condition of oppression,
historical perspectives

00:43:08.850 --> 00:43:11.660
and cultural resources
from which to respond

00:43:11.660 --> 00:43:14.950
as indigenous peoples
that all native peoples

00:43:14.950 --> 00:43:18.980
in the America shared
was the category, Indios.

00:43:18.980 --> 00:43:22.760
And so, they began a two-fold
effort of, one, reappropriating

00:43:22.760 --> 00:43:27.190
and redefining on their terms
a pejorative category arguably

00:43:27.190 --> 00:43:31.070
much like [inaudible] did with
term mestizo in the 19th century

00:43:31.070 --> 00:43:34.910
for the ideology of La Raza
to elaborate a distinctively

00:43:34.910 --> 00:43:38.230
but hemispherically
Teologia india.

00:43:38.230 --> 00:43:41.490
And two, to begin to specify
a move beyond the category

00:43:41.490 --> 00:43:44.870
of Indio for the elaboration
of particular theologies

00:43:44.870 --> 00:43:48.340
of distinct peoples like
a particular Maya theology

00:43:48.340 --> 00:43:51.780
or even more specific, a K'iche
theology, a Tzeltal theology,

00:43:51.780 --> 00:43:55.070
a Q'anjo'bal theology,
Tzotzil theology, et cetera.

00:43:55.070 --> 00:43:58.270
What has been proposed
here is not

00:43:58.270 --> 00:44:01.450
that there is any direct link
between Vico's Theologia Indorum

00:44:01.450 --> 00:44:04.900
and the writings of Highland
Maya elites in the 16th century

00:44:04.900 --> 00:44:07.080
and the current efforts
by indigenous peoples

00:44:07.080 --> 00:44:09.070
to develop Christian
understandings

00:44:09.070 --> 00:44:11.680
on their own cultural
and spiritual terms

00:44:11.680 --> 00:44:14.230
in the movement they
called, Teologia India.

00:44:14.230 --> 00:44:16.710
In fact I find it quite ironic
that I can literally count

00:44:16.710 --> 00:44:19.030
on my hand, actually
a couple of fingers,

00:44:19.030 --> 00:44:22.410
the number of academic
Latin Americans involved

00:44:22.410 --> 00:44:27.250
in Teologia India who even know
who Vico is or was and neither

00:44:27.250 --> 00:44:30.380
of them have actually
read anything by Vico

00:44:30.380 --> 00:44:32.340
because they don't know K'iche.

00:44:32.340 --> 00:44:35.970
Any explicit textual dots
to connect between the 1550s

00:44:35.970 --> 00:44:39.610
and the 1970s is too
vague and spread thin.

00:44:39.610 --> 00:44:42.990
So any legacy of Vico lies
not in the written record

00:44:42.990 --> 00:44:46.560
of later clergy or Maya but
rather at best implicitly

00:44:46.560 --> 00:44:50.170
in the local traditions of
how Maya leaders continued

00:44:50.170 --> 00:44:52.400
to navigate between
their indigenous

00:44:52.400 --> 00:44:55.600
and their Christian
understandings.

00:44:55.600 --> 00:45:00.590
But at the very least, a
thicker ethnohistorical context,

00:45:00.590 --> 00:45:03.390
based on intratextual
analysis of the wider corpus

00:45:03.390 --> 00:45:06.050
of K'ichean writings
by both mendicants

00:45:06.050 --> 00:45:09.160
and Maya provides a
diachronic lens through which

00:45:09.160 --> 00:45:12.270
to read current trends in
Latin American religion

00:45:12.270 --> 00:45:15.820
and thus further reevaluate
the continued agency

00:45:15.820 --> 00:45:20.510
and intellect of, well, Indios.

00:45:20.510 --> 00:45:25.500
[ Applause ]

00:45:37.620 --> 00:45:39.540
&gt;&gt; Ralph Bauer: Thank
you, Garry.

00:45:39.540 --> 00:45:42.590
Our third speaker will be
John Tutino who is a professor

00:45:42.590 --> 00:45:45.490
of history and international
affairs as well as the director

00:45:45.490 --> 00:45:48.970
of the Americas Initiative
at Georgetown University,

00:45:48.970 --> 00:45:51.300
