00:49:16.610 --> 00:49:20.070
of a book entitled
Mexico City, 1808,

00:49:20.070 --> 00:49:24.830
which I tell people is the book
no one will believe Tutino wrote

00:49:24.830 --> 00:49:32.100
because it is urban,
political and short [laughter].

00:49:32.100 --> 00:49:36.850
And I have never fallen into
any of those traps before.

00:49:36.850 --> 00:49:39.340
But I'm trying and I have
succeeded, it's going to publish

00:49:39.340 --> 00:49:42.840
to less than 200 pages
of readable text.

00:49:42.840 --> 00:49:47.360
So I count it a triumph.

00:49:47.360 --> 00:49:52.960
"The Mexican Heartland"
book very much focuses

00:49:52.960 --> 00:49:57.560
on the rural communities of
the basins around Mexico City,

00:49:57.560 --> 00:50:01.820
precisely to distinguish it
from the Bajio that I wrote

00:50:01.820 --> 00:50:05.400
about in making a new world.

00:50:05.400 --> 00:50:08.510
The Mexico City book focuses

00:50:08.510 --> 00:50:12.660
on a pivotal moment
of regime change.

00:50:12.660 --> 00:50:14.730
From what-- And this is
really what I'm going

00:50:14.730 --> 00:50:16.170
to focus on today.

00:50:16.170 --> 00:50:22.010
From a regime that ruled
primarily by mediation backed

00:50:22.010 --> 00:50:28.640
by claims of divine
sovereignty to a lesser regime,

00:50:28.640 --> 00:50:31.090
and I want to call
it more a state,

00:50:31.090 --> 00:50:35.470
that ruled by military
assertion backed by claims

00:50:35.470 --> 00:50:37.280
of popular sovereignty.

00:50:37.280 --> 00:50:40.330
And I'm not going to get into
the transition today other

00:50:40.330 --> 00:50:43.850
than to say one of the things
the book tries to do is point

00:50:43.850 --> 00:50:49.060
out that the shift came in 1808,
before the wars of independence.

00:50:49.060 --> 00:50:52.940
The turn is part of the
stimulus to the conflicts.

00:50:52.940 --> 00:50:56.420
It is not a result
of the conflicts.

00:50:56.420 --> 00:50:58.230
That's not for today.

00:50:58.230 --> 00:51:03.790
What I want to emphasize
today is that both projects,

00:51:03.790 --> 00:51:05.330
the Mexican Heartland project

00:51:05.330 --> 00:51:08.400
and the Mexico City
1808 project,

00:51:08.400 --> 00:51:15.790
required me to push forward
on a rethinking of the nature

00:51:15.790 --> 00:51:19.040
of the Spanish regime
in New Spain.

00:51:19.040 --> 00:51:23.000
Over the long haul, and
particularly prior to 1760

00:51:23.000 --> 00:51:28.780
in the coming of the
Bourbon assertions and thus

00:51:28.780 --> 00:51:33.760
to rethink the impact
of what we too--

00:51:33.760 --> 00:51:35.740
we call the Bourbon reforms

00:51:35.740 --> 00:51:39.720
that hit New Spain
hardest from the 1760s.

00:51:39.720 --> 00:51:44.770
And my emphasis there is that
that impact was far more limited

00:51:44.770 --> 00:51:48.010
than we have often
taken it to be.

00:51:48.010 --> 00:51:52.370
But today, I want to focus
on my emerging understanding

00:51:52.370 --> 00:51:58.250
of the regime of more
or less 1550 to 1750

00:51:58.250 --> 00:52:01.990
and its pivotal role
in sustaining

00:52:01.990 --> 00:52:09.500
and stabilizing a silver economy
that funded Spain's empire

00:52:09.500 --> 00:52:15.480
that drove global
trades and focusing on it

00:52:15.480 --> 00:52:19.680
in what I have dubbed the
Mexican Heartland a region

00:52:19.680 --> 00:52:24.030
grounded in enduring
self-governing landed

00:52:24.030 --> 00:52:27.510
indigenous communities.

00:52:27.510 --> 00:52:31.210
My argument and in
the original title is

00:52:31.210 --> 00:52:37.880
that it is an old
regime sustaining,

00:52:37.880 --> 00:52:41.750
promoting a new economy.

00:52:41.750 --> 00:52:49.750
I use old regime very explicitly
as the English variant

00:52:49.750 --> 00:52:53.990
of what Europeans would
call an ancien regime.

00:52:53.990 --> 00:52:59.440
An ancien regime tied

00:52:59.440 --> 00:53:04.940
to an economy becoming ever more
capitalist and that the fusion

00:53:04.940 --> 00:53:09.640
of them is what matters.

00:53:09.640 --> 00:53:15.960
And I'm going to argue that both
the ancien regime as it evolved

00:53:15.960 --> 00:53:19.250
in New Spain was a hybrid.

00:53:19.250 --> 00:53:21.910
The new economy as it evolved

00:53:21.910 --> 00:53:25.990
in the Mesoamerican
regions was a hybrid

00:53:25.990 --> 00:53:29.760
and thus the fusion
is a double hybrid.

00:53:29.760 --> 00:53:33.640
Let me try to make the case.

00:53:33.640 --> 00:53:37.070
And you'll quickly see
that I am building upon

00:53:37.070 --> 00:53:43.460
and giving my own twist to a lot
of work by colleagues I admire.

00:53:43.460 --> 00:53:48.040
So on the ancien regime
following the work

00:53:48.040 --> 00:53:53.230
of Alejandro Caneque, following
Ernesto Sanchez de Tagle,

00:53:53.230 --> 00:53:57.760
whose work is mostly known
in Mexico, following the work

00:53:57.760 --> 00:54:02.880
of Annick Lempérière,
and also following the work

00:54:02.880 --> 00:54:08.560
of my colleague Jim Collins
who has argued for decades

00:54:08.560 --> 00:54:13.970
that what is called
absolutism in France

00:54:13.970 --> 00:54:20.830
and Europe is overunderstood as
coercive and needs to be seen

00:54:20.830 --> 00:54:25.950
in very different more
negotiating mediating ways.

00:54:25.950 --> 00:54:31.910
I see the regime that emerged
in New Spain after about 1550

00:54:31.910 --> 00:54:37.100
as a classic ancien
regime in key ways.

00:54:37.100 --> 00:54:39.810
It is based on multiple
corporations

00:54:39.810 --> 00:54:44.800
and institutions sanctioned
with multiple rights

00:54:44.800 --> 00:54:52.000
and laws integrated and overseen
by a regime that focuses

00:54:52.000 --> 00:54:57.110
on mediation, sometimes
judicial, sometimes political,

00:54:57.110 --> 00:55:00.560
but everything is
a balancing act.

00:55:00.560 --> 00:55:05.650
And it does that and you can
play with the cause and effect

00:55:05.650 --> 00:55:09.120
because certainly in the
interior of New Spain,

00:55:09.120 --> 00:55:15.820
it is a regime with notably
limited coercive capacities.

00:55:15.820 --> 00:55:23.090
It has very little ability to
force anybody to do anything

00:55:23.090 --> 00:55:29.580
and thus it turned to force
only as a last resort,

00:55:29.580 --> 00:55:34.110
and it understands that
if everything I've said

00:55:34.110 --> 00:55:38.960
to that fits the model of the
scholars I have listed I think

00:55:38.960 --> 00:55:43.420
in terms of being an Ancien
regime in the New World.

00:55:43.420 --> 00:55:51.890
But I want to emphasize, in New
Spain, it is very much a hybrid

00:55:51.890 --> 00:56:00.270
because it was grounded in the
creation of literally thousands,

00:56:00.270 --> 00:56:04.600
one good Mexican scholar
has had it over 4000,

00:56:04.600 --> 00:56:10.350
indigenous republics with rights
to land and self-rule built

00:56:10.350 --> 00:56:15.960
on the remnants of the
indigenous altepetl ruled

00:56:15.960 --> 00:56:19.160
by native notables
adapting variants

00:56:19.160 --> 00:56:23.300
of what I just generically
call indigenous Christianities.

00:56:23.300 --> 00:56:28.340
I don't think very far from
where Garry is going here.

00:56:28.340 --> 00:56:33.180
And that operate with
sanctioned rights to mediations

00:56:33.180 --> 00:56:36.360
through special courts.

00:56:37.370 --> 00:56:42.890
What perhaps, this I
offer speculatively,

00:56:42.890 --> 00:56:47.970
made this hybrid a
particularly unique variant

00:56:47.970 --> 00:56:55.650
of an ancien regime is what--
is really the extreme dearth

00:56:55.650 --> 00:57:02.330
of military power on
the ground in New Span.

00:57:02.330 --> 00:57:06.490
If-- As my colleague Jim
Collins has detailed,

00:57:06.490 --> 00:57:11.220
the French ancien regime
mediated first and coerced only

00:57:11.220 --> 00:57:15.200
when pressed when it had to.

00:57:15.200 --> 00:57:19.290
There was no dearth of
coercive force in Europe.

00:57:19.290 --> 00:57:24.160
War guaranteed that there
were coercive forces around

00:57:24.160 --> 00:57:27.700
and available, sometimes one
wonders, a little more dispersed

00:57:27.700 --> 00:57:30.690
than we sometimes think.

00:57:30.690 --> 00:57:36.370
In New Spain after 1550 in
the Mesoamerican regions,

00:57:36.370 --> 00:57:40.740
after 1600 in the end of what
are called the Chichimeca wars

00:57:40.740 --> 00:57:43.470
in the Bajio and regions north,

00:57:43.470 --> 00:57:47.610
the indigenous majority
was disarmed.

00:57:47.610 --> 00:57:49.790
That's famously known.

00:57:49.790 --> 00:57:55.100
Less often recognized is the
Spanish regime essentially

00:57:55.100 --> 00:58:00.310
disarmed too and
relied on what I had--

00:58:00.310 --> 00:58:03.880
best can call minimal
and uncertain malicious.

00:58:03.880 --> 00:58:06.290
Certainly not controlled,
funded or commanded

00:58:06.290 --> 00:58:09.800
by anybody in the regime.

00:58:09.800 --> 00:58:14.070
Now, again, there
were military efforts.

00:58:14.070 --> 00:58:18.330
But the Spanish empire's
military activity focused first

00:58:18.330 --> 00:58:22.770
on a naval protection
of trade and on holding

00:58:22.770 --> 00:58:25.730
in New Spain the far
northern frontiers

00:58:25.730 --> 00:58:29.440
and I will quickly note that
in the latter its success was

00:58:29.440 --> 00:58:31.180
pretty limited too.

00:58:31.180 --> 00:58:33.900
It didn't have all that
much effective force

00:58:33.900 --> 00:58:36.670
in the far north as well.

00:58:37.890 --> 00:58:43.230
So if I'm right, the question
becomes, how could a regime

00:58:43.230 --> 00:58:47.830
with such limited coercive
powers be sustained

00:58:47.830 --> 00:58:49.360
for centuries?

00:58:49.360 --> 00:58:53.360
And I want to argue, there are
really two key factors looking

00:58:53.360 --> 00:58:55.210
behind this.

00:58:55.210 --> 00:59:00.630
The first is, I don't
know how else to put it,

00:59:00.630 --> 00:59:04.640
the greatest calamity of
contact and conquest was--

00:59:04.640 --> 00:59:08.540
became the basis for the
underlying success of the regime

00:59:08.540 --> 00:59:11.830
that followed, and that
is the depopulation.

00:59:11.830 --> 00:59:14.880
That by the late 16th century,

00:59:16.280 --> 00:59:22.840
resources are astonishingly
ample

00:59:22.840 --> 00:59:27.990
to a radically shrunken
surviving native populations

00:59:27.990 --> 00:59:34.720
organized in the new indigenous
republics and also to Europeans

00:59:34.720 --> 00:59:36.980
who are building
commercial states,

00:59:36.980 --> 00:59:39.570
other commercial activities.

00:59:39.570 --> 00:59:44.940
It is in that context
that Woodrow Borah,

00:59:44.940 --> 00:59:48.980
Brian Owensby have documented
for the 16th and 17th century,

00:59:48.980 --> 00:59:51.840
William Taylor for
the 18th century

00:59:51.840 --> 00:59:55.690
that overwhelmingly indigenous--

00:59:55.690 --> 00:59:57.790
indigenous republic

00:59:57.790 --> 01:00:00.580
to indigenous republic
relations had conflicts,

01:00:00.580 --> 01:00:05.680
indigenous republic
and Spanish officials,

01:00:05.680 --> 01:00:11.560
merchant conflicts were
mediated in the court.

01:00:12.680 --> 01:00:15.060
And the ability of the courts

01:00:15.060 --> 01:00:19.770
to mediate legitimated the
continuity of the regime.

01:00:19.770 --> 01:00:25.750
So the depopulation creates
an environment, a true rarity,

01:00:25.750 --> 01:00:31.600
I would say in modern history,
in which resources are scarce

01:00:31.600 --> 01:00:35.370
for almost no one
for a period of time

01:00:35.370 --> 01:00:39.150
and the regime consolidates
in that context.

01:00:39.150 --> 01:00:42.440
Simultaneously-- and the
intersection may be even more

01:00:42.440 --> 01:00:45.270
rare historically.

01:00:45.270 --> 01:00:52.070
The opportunity of silver from
the 1550s created possibility

01:00:52.070 --> 01:00:55.680
of profits for merchant
financiers, for mine operators,

01:00:55.680 --> 01:00:59.550
for commercial estate
growers, and no shortage

01:00:59.550 --> 01:01:01.970
of resources to do it.

01:01:01.970 --> 01:01:06.320
But also we sometimes don't
recognize enough opportunities

01:01:06.320 --> 01:01:09.210
to market produce
and gain wage income

01:01:09.210 --> 01:01:11.910
for indigenous peoples inside

01:01:11.910 --> 01:01:16.140
and outside the indigenous
republics.

01:01:16.140 --> 01:01:22.520
And in that context, society

01:01:22.520 --> 01:01:28.270
of Spanish Mesoamerica is
integrated by an ancien regime

01:01:28.270 --> 01:01:33.940
that used negotiated processes
of petition and mediation

01:01:33.940 --> 01:01:40.760
to balance interests among the
powerful and used the courts

01:01:40.760 --> 01:01:43.950
to mediate disputes among
indigenous communities

01:01:43.950 --> 01:01:46.920
between indigenous communities
and states and merchants,

01:01:46.920 --> 01:01:51.590
et cetera, all backed
by exceptionally limited

01:01:51.590 --> 01:01:53.870
and uncertain militias.

01:01:53.870 --> 01:02:00.580
I have almost gotten-- it
is so regular for scholars,

01:02:00.580 --> 01:02:05.140
students to just-- it's a
language that comes to all of us

01:02:05.140 --> 01:02:09.300
so naturally, the Spanish
forced, the Spanish coerced,

01:02:09.300 --> 01:02:11.380
the Spanish made it happen.

01:02:11.380 --> 01:02:16.120
And I say, wait a minute, tell
me-- They may have ordered,

01:02:16.120 --> 01:02:19.680
they may have mandated but
find me the coercive power,

01:02:19.680 --> 01:02:22.460
where is it in the
neighborhood that that happened?

01:02:22.460 --> 01:02:24.530
And I haven't gotten
many answers

01:02:24.530 --> 01:02:26.030
that it's actually there.

01:02:26.030 --> 01:02:29.980
Something else is going
on and I'm searching

01:02:29.980 --> 01:02:32.380
for a way to understand it.

01:02:32.380 --> 01:02:35.170
All right.

01:02:35.170 --> 01:02:41.470
That hybrid ancien regime, my
argument is, sustain an economy,

01:02:41.470 --> 01:02:43.540
I increasingly describe

01:02:43.540 --> 01:02:47.790
as silver capitalism
by the 18th century.

01:02:47.790 --> 01:02:53.920
And in Mesoamerica, I want
to emphasize, particularly

01:02:53.920 --> 01:02:58.480
in the core basins around Mexico
City, my Mexican Heartland,

01:02:58.480 --> 01:03:03.730
that silver capitalism
was also a hybrid.

01:03:03.730 --> 01:03:08.700
Finance, commerce concentrated
in the capital, in the city,

01:03:08.700 --> 01:03:12.240
as did the wealthy
families leading mining,

01:03:12.240 --> 01:03:16.810
landed entrepreneurs, they're
concentrated in the oligarchy

01:03:16.810 --> 01:03:21.590
as capitalist as any in the
world in the 18th century.

01:03:24.170 --> 01:03:27.750
The distinction, in the
Bajio in the regions north,

01:03:27.750 --> 01:03:30.770
the subject of my Making
a New World, this is owns

01:03:30.770 --> 01:03:34.930
with few landed self-governing
native republics.

01:03:34.930 --> 01:03:38.080
Commercial capitalist
ways, the new economy,

01:03:38.080 --> 01:03:45.810
shaped life all the way to
the base, top to bottom.

01:03:45.810 --> 01:03:50.990
From the 17th century
through the 18th, mineworkers,

01:03:50.990 --> 01:03:53.290
tenant-growers, wage
workers in fields

01:03:53.290 --> 01:03:56.040
and factories including
the thousands of women

01:03:56.040 --> 01:03:58.310
in the great tobacco
factories in Mexico City

01:03:58.310 --> 01:04:02.550
and Queretaro live
in a commercial--

01:04:02.550 --> 01:04:05.930
I think rapidly becoming
capitalist society.

01:04:05.930 --> 01:04:10.160
But in the Mexican heartland,
the Mesoamerican heartland

01:04:10.160 --> 01:04:15.310
at this point, outside
the city and mining towns,

01:04:15.310 --> 01:04:18.220
the vast majority
of the population,

01:04:18.220 --> 01:04:22.360
90% live in indigenous
republics,

01:04:22.360 --> 01:04:27.190
speaking indigenous languages,
Nahuatl or Otomi in most cases,

01:04:27.190 --> 01:04:30.650
through to the end
of the 18th century.

01:04:30.650 --> 01:04:36.050
While their populations had
been low and lands were ample,

01:04:36.050 --> 01:04:40.060
late 16th through
the 17th century,

01:04:40.060 --> 01:04:43.380
people of the republics had
basically had the capacity

01:04:43.380 --> 01:04:47.420
to sustain themselves and
to take wage supplements,

01:04:47.420 --> 01:04:54.110
market earnings at mines in the
states providing for the city.

01:04:54.110 --> 01:04:58.280
After 1700, population
begins to grow,

01:04:58.280 --> 01:05:01.680
land becomes less efficient

01:05:01.680 --> 01:05:06.500
but not radically
scarce in the republics.

01:05:11.290 --> 01:05:15.820
And it becomes less possible
for families and communities

01:05:15.820 --> 01:05:19.040
to maintain the autonomous
production of sustenance

01:05:19.040 --> 01:05:22.250
that had marked them
post-depopulation

01:05:22.250 --> 01:05:24.940
through the 17th century.

01:05:24.940 --> 01:05:33.030
But in the 18th century, as
Spanish entrepreneurs took

01:05:33.030 --> 01:05:37.680
over the commercial
production of indigenous crops,

01:05:37.680 --> 01:05:41.850
indigenous crops, maize and
pulque, were primarily produced

01:05:41.850 --> 01:05:44.640
by indigenous community
based growers

01:05:44.640 --> 01:05:46.380
through the 17th century.

01:05:46.380 --> 01:05:51.800
From about the 1720s, major
landed entrepreneurs based

01:05:51.800 --> 01:05:55.420
in Mexico City took
over production of--

01:05:55.420 --> 01:05:57.880
commercial production
of maize and pulque.

01:05:57.880 --> 01:06:01.880
They took over the
Mexico City pulquerias.

01:06:01.880 --> 01:06:07.660
And they create-- while
they profit wonderfully,

01:06:07.660 --> 01:06:16.390
their capitalist utopia,
they offer increasing amounts

01:06:16.390 --> 01:06:19.340
of wage labor at their estates

01:06:19.340 --> 01:06:22.270
to sustain families
and communities.

01:06:22.270 --> 01:06:27.730
So, people are capable, are able
and they do remain residents,

01:06:27.730 --> 01:06:31.600
vicino, citizens of the
indigenous republics.

01:06:31.600 --> 01:06:34.470
They produce sustenance
to the extent they can.

01:06:34.470 --> 01:06:38.750
But as they can't, they
increasingly cap the income

01:06:38.750 --> 01:06:43.250
of the commercial economy
through some marketing,

01:06:43.250 --> 01:06:45.280
but ever more through
wage labor.

01:06:45.280 --> 01:06:48.600
And in the process, it
sustains the republics

01:06:48.600 --> 01:06:49.900
and their families.

01:06:49.900 --> 01:06:54.010
And in fact through the
18th century, subsidizes

01:06:54.010 --> 01:06:58.770
and sustains a growing
commercial silver capitalism.

01:06:58.770 --> 01:07:00.460
They're actually essential

01:07:00.460 --> 01:07:05.850
to its endurance
and profit ability.

01:07:05.850 --> 01:07:11.220
Simple characterization
of a complex problem.

01:07:11.220 --> 01:07:17.560
Production of silver,
the-- international trade,

01:07:17.560 --> 01:07:20.060
the internal commercial economy

01:07:20.060 --> 01:07:25.740
and regime revenues all
grew more than four times

01:07:25.740 --> 01:07:30.670
over in the Mesoamerican
regions of New Spain from 1700

01:07:30.670 --> 01:07:38.750
to 1800 while the population
a little more than doubled.

01:07:38.750 --> 01:07:42.300
And what is too often
not recognized,

01:07:42.300 --> 01:07:49.890
in the Mesoamerican heartland,
stability held past 1800.

01:07:49.890 --> 01:07:53.400
There is no major
destabilizing challenge

01:07:53.400 --> 01:07:59.550
to this regime until 1808, 1810.

01:07:59.550 --> 01:08:02.960
The break I argue came in 1808.

01:08:02.960 --> 01:08:05.370
It came in May in Spain.

01:08:05.370 --> 01:08:09.980
It came July to September
in Mexico City,

01:08:09.980 --> 01:08:15.890
when in the reverberations that
came from Napoleon's invasion.

01:08:15.890 --> 01:08:21.240
Politics were militarized
in Spain and in New Spain.

01:08:21.240 --> 01:08:25.620
And the militarization
of politics came coupled

01:08:25.620 --> 01:08:28.270
with claims of popular
sovereignty.

01:08:28.270 --> 01:08:33.010
And I will simply say, that
has set me to thinking a lot

01:08:33.010 --> 01:08:36.660
about a rethinking of the
19th and 20th century.

01:08:36.660 --> 01:08:39.960
But that's a new and different
history and I'm just going

01:08:39.960 --> 01:08:42.510
to say thank you very much.

01:08:42.510 --> 01:08:46.500
