01:12:01.760 --> 01:12:03.060
&gt;&gt; Garry Sparks:
So, the relationship

01:12:03.060 --> 01:12:04.360
between liberation theology

01:12:04.360 --> 01:12:06.220
and enculturation theology
particularly in New Spain

01:12:06.220 --> 01:12:07.840
or Latin America-- Turn it on.

01:12:07.840 --> 01:12:11.040
I don't know.

01:12:11.040 --> 01:12:12.460
Oh, I'm sorry.

01:12:12.460 --> 01:12:14.930
It's a great question because
there is oftentimes I think a

01:12:14.930 --> 01:12:18.830
false understanding that
there's these three movements

01:12:18.830 --> 01:12:23.910
within current Latin America
and Christian theology initiated

01:12:23.910 --> 01:12:27.050
after Vatican II
liberation theology.

01:12:27.050 --> 01:12:29.560
And then, there's this
conservative reaction against it

01:12:29.560 --> 01:12:32.390
which is the Catholic renewal
or the charismatic theology

01:12:32.390 --> 01:12:38.100
which comes about a bit later in
the 1980s and then the offshoot

01:12:38.100 --> 01:12:41.500
from liberation theology
particularly around 1992

01:12:41.500 --> 01:12:45.180
and the counter-protest
in Columbus' anniversary,

01:12:45.180 --> 01:12:47.980
the 500th anniversary by
indigenous people, the emergence

01:12:47.980 --> 01:12:49.390
of enculturation theology.

01:12:49.390 --> 01:12:52.580
But yet if you look at
the local paper trail,

01:12:52.580 --> 01:12:55.560
really enculturation theology
begins prior to the Second

01:12:55.560 --> 01:12:57.890
Vatican Council in
places like Chiapas,

01:12:57.890 --> 01:13:00.320
the Dominicans mid 1960s,

01:13:00.320 --> 01:13:06.520
liberation theology would
be much more clear in 1971

01:13:06.520 --> 01:13:09.550
and then charismatic renewal
also began simultaneous

01:13:09.550 --> 01:13:11.280
to liberation theology and

01:13:11.280 --> 01:13:14.920
doesn't acquire a conservative
sort of dimension to it

01:13:14.920 --> 01:13:18.040
until late '70s and early
'80s, but they're all

01:13:18.040 --> 01:13:19.470
in concurrent relation--

01:13:19.470 --> 01:13:23.060
movements rather than sort of
splintering off the main trunk.

01:13:23.060 --> 01:13:25.330
The main distinction
though liberation theology

01:13:25.330 --> 01:13:27.670
and enculturation theology is
liberation theology is first

01:13:27.670 --> 01:13:30.060
and foremost concerned
with class analysis.

01:13:30.060 --> 01:13:33.570
So, that's the primary
sort of locus of oppression

01:13:33.570 --> 01:13:36.230
that needs to be addressed.

01:13:36.230 --> 01:13:40.790
Indigenous peoples found that
they find that rather racist.

01:13:40.790 --> 01:13:42.860
And so, reading early
sort of [inaudible]

01:13:42.860 --> 01:13:46.790
by say Leonardo Boff
really sort of tip a hat

01:13:46.790 --> 01:13:50.660
to gender oppression
or ethnic oppression.

01:13:50.660 --> 01:13:53.020
For many indigenous
peoples, once said to me

01:13:53.020 --> 01:13:55.980
by a [inaudible] colleague,
I'm poor because I'm Maya.

01:13:55.980 --> 01:13:58.500
I'm not Maya because I'm poor.

01:13:58.500 --> 01:14:01.890
And then for them, the primary--
the sort of the super structure

01:14:01.890 --> 01:14:04.410
of oppression to put
it in Boff's terms,

01:14:04.410 --> 01:14:09.670
Marxist terms is racism and that
the class oppression is really

01:14:09.670 --> 01:14:11.250
more of the infrastructure.

01:14:11.250 --> 01:14:13.070
And so, they sort of flip it.

01:14:13.070 --> 01:14:15.230
And they also think that
the liberations theology--

01:14:15.230 --> 01:14:18.800
agenda has a bit more
of an assimilationist.

01:14:18.800 --> 01:14:21.690
Most of the advocates for
liberation theology come up

01:14:21.690 --> 01:14:24.100
with liberal political
wing of Latin America

01:14:24.100 --> 01:14:27.320
which typically wants to sort of
assimilate and build in which--

01:14:27.320 --> 01:14:31.820
into mainstream indigenous
people which has a tenor

01:14:31.820 --> 01:14:34.160
of ethnocide for many indigenous

01:14:34.160 --> 01:14:35.460
activists who are trying

01:14:35.460 --> 01:14:38.650
to actually preserve some
[inaudible] other culture.

01:14:38.650 --> 01:14:42.940
So, there's-- in that sense,
they're somewhat shared

01:14:42.940 --> 01:14:45.150
with the common discourse
of [inaudible],

01:14:45.150 --> 01:14:46.450
the elimination of hierarchies

01:14:46.450 --> 01:14:49.810
[inaudible] of egalitarian
horizontal structures as opposed

01:14:49.810 --> 01:14:54.050
to vertical structures,
political, economic, ecclesial.

01:14:54.050 --> 01:14:57.660
But the ways that they think
are the roots of the problem,

01:14:57.660 --> 01:15:01.680
diagnoses, and then
prescriptions

01:15:01.680 --> 01:15:03.670
for that [inaudible].

01:15:03.670 --> 01:15:09.310
I don't know if that's
the question but-- OK.

01:15:09.310 --> 01:15:10.610
Yeah.

01:15:10.610 --> 01:15:11.910
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

01:15:11.910 --> 01:15:14.970
&gt;&gt; John Tutino: Very easily--
Religion, if pivotally central,

01:15:14.970 --> 01:15:17.800
I could easily make it
the third hybridity.

01:15:17.800 --> 01:15:19.950
If I argue for a
regime hybridity

01:15:19.950 --> 01:15:21.250
and economic hybridity,

01:15:21.250 --> 01:15:24.440
certainly there is a
religious hybridity embedded

01:15:24.440 --> 01:15:26.230
in all of these.

01:15:26.230 --> 01:15:28.520
And I'll first escape
the question

01:15:28.520 --> 01:15:30.060
with the highest
praise I can think of.

01:15:30.060 --> 01:15:32.700
It made no sense for me
to add that hybridity

01:15:32.700 --> 01:15:35.890
because that is the issue that
Serge Gruzinski has addressed

01:15:35.890 --> 01:15:39.220
in such great depth and
detail for New Spain.

01:15:39.220 --> 01:15:44.390
I don't have much to add there
other than to learn from you.

01:15:44.390 --> 01:15:51.320
But I'll characterize my view
of this right now in two moments

01:15:51.320 --> 01:15:54.270
in a pretty broad
overly general way.

01:15:54.270 --> 01:15:58.260
First, looking at the end of
the 16th, early 17th century,

01:15:58.260 --> 01:16:00.810
the moment on which I
see this system sort

01:16:00.810 --> 01:16:03.300
of consolidating
for the first time.

01:16:03.300 --> 01:16:05.420
And two things come
together there

01:16:05.420 --> 01:16:07.570
that have really struck me.

01:16:07.570 --> 01:16:11.540
If you look at the
communities, almost everybody

01:16:11.540 --> 01:16:15.370
in the indigenous republics,
they're not speaking Spanish.

01:16:15.370 --> 01:16:18.870
But in the areas certainly
anywhere close to Mexico City,

01:16:18.870 --> 01:16:21.890
everyone is taking Cristiano.

01:16:21.890 --> 01:16:27.320
They are self-defining
themselves as Christian.

01:16:27.320 --> 01:16:32.660
At the same time, the
clerical discourse,

01:16:32.660 --> 01:16:35.870
shall we say the tired
missionary class,

01:16:35.870 --> 01:16:38.710
is writing about their failure.

01:16:38.710 --> 01:16:44.240
They have not created Christians
in their definitional sense.

01:16:44.240 --> 01:16:46.840
And to me, that mixes
everything,

01:16:46.840 --> 01:16:50.280
that indigenous peoples
have adapted, evolved

01:16:50.280 --> 01:16:53.900
and consolidated their
vision, their understanding

01:16:53.900 --> 01:16:56.040
of what Christianity
is and should be

01:16:56.040 --> 01:16:59.080
as it's meaningful to them.

01:16:59.080 --> 01:17:03.190
They're developing their
devotions to virgin, saints,

01:17:03.190 --> 01:17:06.450
the cofradias that sustain
them, et cetera, et cetera.

01:17:06.450 --> 01:17:08.660
And at the same time,

01:17:08.660 --> 01:17:11.050
it is pretty clear
there was a resistance

01:17:11.050 --> 01:17:15.040
to European notions
of sin and morality.

01:17:15.040 --> 01:17:20.130
So it is a very much hybridized
religion that I have just come--

01:17:20.130 --> 01:17:23.070
and I use it in the plural
indigenous Christianities.

01:17:23.070 --> 01:17:25.330
There may be one
for every community.

01:17:25.330 --> 01:17:28.350
This is not a broadly
shared reality.

01:17:28.350 --> 01:17:36.150
And that the whole system had to
live by the religious hierarchy

01:17:36.150 --> 01:17:38.690
and the regime learning
to accept all

01:17:38.690 --> 01:17:43.200
of that diverse hybridity
at the local level.

01:17:43.200 --> 01:17:47.750
The classic best known
example of course is we know

01:17:47.750 --> 01:17:51.520
when devotion to Guadalupe
emerges in the regions

01:17:51.520 --> 01:17:56.020
of Mexico City, it is
resisted by the powerful

01:17:56.020 --> 01:17:58.430
for the earlier century
and there's a point

01:17:58.430 --> 01:18:01.610
in the mid 17th century where
it can't be resisted so we might

01:18:01.610 --> 01:18:04.260
as well adapt and
promote, et cetera.

01:18:04.260 --> 01:18:05.710
And the regime goes forward

01:18:05.710 --> 01:18:08.030
in that mixed negotiated
hybrid way.

01:18:08.030 --> 01:18:11.520
And then I'll just add,
get to the 18th century,

01:18:11.520 --> 01:18:13.610
and here you have
what [inaudible]

01:18:13.610 --> 01:18:17.290
so clearly the Magistrates
of the Sacred.

01:18:17.290 --> 01:18:24.130
Yes, bourbon reformers wanted
to impose a new more moralizing,

01:18:24.130 --> 01:18:29.590
more true Christianity
on the communities.

01:18:29.590 --> 01:18:32.070
And what he found were
letter after letter written

01:18:32.070 --> 01:18:34.190
by those [inaudible]
saying, if I do that,

01:18:34.190 --> 01:18:35.490
they won't pay my fees.

01:18:35.490 --> 01:18:37.050
If I do that, they'll
run me out of town.

01:18:37.050 --> 01:18:38.810
I cannot do that.

01:18:38.810 --> 01:18:41.200
I have to accept
the Christianity

01:18:41.200 --> 01:18:43.740
that is-- that is there.

01:18:43.740 --> 01:18:47.180
That's my short tale
of the third hybridity,

01:18:47.180 --> 01:18:49.480
but it is very much
a hybrid too.

01:18:50.500 --> 01:18:52.840
&gt;&gt; Ralph Bauer: OK,
may-- one more question.

01:18:52.840 --> 01:18:55.480
OK, please.

01:18:55.480 --> 01:19:01.510
&gt;&gt; Does the hybridization of
the religion in the 20th century

01:19:01.510 --> 01:19:08.190
impact the Indian community
as it slides, you know,

01:19:08.190 --> 01:19:12.880
adapt their agricultural
technology in Guatemala?

01:19:12.880 --> 01:19:14.180
&gt;&gt; Garry Sparks: I'm sorry.

01:19:14.180 --> 01:19:15.480
I missed the first part
of the question, sir.

01:19:15.480 --> 01:19:17.840
&gt;&gt; Does the hybridization
of religion

01:19:17.840 --> 01:19:24.930
in the Indian communities
impact the efforts on the part

01:19:24.930 --> 01:19:29.780
of the Indian community to move
towards the new agriculture?

01:19:35.600 --> 01:19:37.410
&gt;&gt; Garry Sparks: I
don't-- I don't think so.

01:19:37.410 --> 01:19:41.300
I mean, I just say, I'm
reticent to sort of buy

01:19:41.300 --> 01:19:44.310
into anything distinctively
hybrid

01:19:44.310 --> 01:19:49.070
about the Christianity in, say,
Mesoamerica, Guatemala given the

01:19:49.070 --> 01:19:50.500
fact that we put up a Yule tree

01:19:50.500 --> 01:19:54.440
around the Roman Saturnalia
festival Christmas and look

01:19:54.440 --> 01:19:57.400
for Easter eggs on the
fertility festival.

01:19:57.400 --> 01:19:58.700
Easter--

01:19:58.700 --> 01:20:01.070
I mean, Christianity is kind
of a hybridity, all going down,

01:20:01.070 --> 01:20:02.370
right, sort of all going
down in that sense.

01:20:02.370 --> 01:20:05.590
So I'm not entirely convinced
Maya have ever really been doing

01:20:05.590 --> 01:20:09.370
things different than say Celts
in Ireland or even Palestinians

01:20:09.370 --> 01:20:15.100
for the past 2000 years,
Palestinian Christians.

01:20:15.100 --> 01:20:19.330
But no, I mean, if you
can look at things like--

01:20:19.330 --> 01:20:22.140
I mean, just probably
like as interesting

01:20:22.140 --> 01:20:23.440
as the text is [inaudible]
where she talked

01:20:23.440 --> 01:20:25.150
about her father working
in the Peace Corps

01:20:25.150 --> 01:20:28.760
in order to implement new
sort of farming techniques and

01:20:28.760 --> 01:20:33.040
yet she is trying harvest
a particular distinctively

01:20:33.040 --> 01:20:37.510
indigenous identity with about
13 of her chapters beginning

01:20:37.510 --> 01:20:41.160
with epigraphs, The
Book of Rule.

01:20:41.160 --> 01:20:44.410
And so I think for many of them,
I think they're negotiating a,

01:20:44.410 --> 01:20:48.110
you know, both modern
technology, modernity

01:20:48.110 --> 01:20:51.460
today just as they were
negotiating modernity

01:20:51.460 --> 01:20:57.300
with cofradias and
[inaudible] 500 years ago.

01:20:57.300 --> 01:21:04.280
And many of the-- particularly
say 1950s, 1960s authors

01:21:04.280 --> 01:21:05.580
that are bringing in--

01:21:05.580 --> 01:21:07.900
some agents that are
bringing in modern technology,

01:21:07.900 --> 01:21:09.730
Maryknoll priests
are also bringing

01:21:09.730 --> 01:21:11.340
in liberation theology, right.

01:21:11.340 --> 01:21:13.720
So [inaudible] cardamom
production in [inaudible] and

01:21:13.720 --> 01:21:19.280
yet sort of what's happening
with also Jesuits in that area

01:21:19.280 --> 01:21:21.280
of enculturation theology.

01:21:21.280 --> 01:21:24.290
And of course, Guatemala is one
of the larger producers of--

01:21:24.290 --> 01:21:26.650
and exporters of
cardamom [inaudible].

01:21:27.780 --> 01:21:30.360
Yeah, very politicized
liberationist

01:21:30.360 --> 01:21:33.430
or you can say [inaudible],
very active with Jesuits,

01:21:33.430 --> 01:21:38.180
and so they're combining
Christian identity,

01:21:38.180 --> 01:21:40.120
that might be.

01:21:40.120 --> 01:21:42.000
So I don't think
they see them anyway

01:21:42.000 --> 01:21:47.320
that is mutually
exclusive necessarily.

01:21:47.320 --> 01:21:49.050
Are you-- Is there a
particular concrete example?

01:21:49.050 --> 01:21:53.650
&gt;&gt; Well, I was thinking the
fact that in the 16th century,

01:21:53.650 --> 01:21:56.150
indigenous community, a lot

01:21:56.150 --> 01:21:59.590
of different indigenous
community I know begin to look

01:21:59.590 --> 01:22:04.120
at the use of fertilizer
in a different way.

01:22:04.120 --> 01:22:13.480
And I think that was a part of
their ability to see fertilizer

01:22:13.480 --> 01:22:18.090
from a different vantage point
in terms of what was happening

01:22:18.090 --> 01:22:20.110
in relation to [inaudible]

01:22:20.110 --> 01:22:23.090
because at one time, it was
very difficult to get them

01:22:23.090 --> 01:22:26.260
to change their survival
agricultural habit.

01:22:26.260 --> 01:22:28.640
I mean-- Right.

01:22:28.640 --> 01:22:29.940
So that's what--

01:22:29.940 --> 01:22:31.240
&gt;&gt; Garry Sparks: I think it also
have to do with the local sort

01:22:31.240 --> 01:22:32.900
of political tension
particularly in that period

01:22:32.900 --> 01:22:35.910
